<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Wrestling Grows As a Sport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At 5 feet tall and about 115 pounds, Patricia  
Miranda doesn't think of herself as scary -- except when she has to 
be. 
</P>
<P>
	She knows she can intimidate women, men and teen-age boys.  
</P>
<P>
	The Stanford University sophomore is a nationally ranked  
wrestler. And like most other female wrestlers, when she isn't 
matched against females, she's matched against males. She started 
wrestling boys in the eighth grade. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did a trial run and really liked it -- and why not?'' Miranda  
said. ``It was a sport that took all of me. What intrigued me most 
was the mental challenge. Almost all of it was mind games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wrestling is not beyond women, Miranda said. ``If the woman  
feels she can compete on the male level, it is possible, especially 
in high school,'' she said. ``Women are weaker, just by physiology 
-- but they can train and have more speed and be more focused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miranda is ranked No.2 on the women's national team sponsored by  
USA Wrestling, the U.S. amateur governing body. Although she can 
wrestle in international competitions against women, there is no 
Olympic women's competition. The sport might be included in the 
2004 Summer Games, said Mike Duroe, the team's national 
developmental coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Females are a small minority of U.S. wrestlers, but they are a  
growing minority. Their trouble is that, with some exceptions, 
there still are too few females in one place to create female 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	At the high school level, around 1,900 girls participated in the  
1997-98 school year, compared with more than 229,000 boys, 
according to the National Federation of State High School 
Associations, which tracks high school sports participation. In the 
first year in which girls' participation was surveyed, 1984-85, 
there were six, said federation spokesman Bruce Howard. 
</P>
<P>
	When they can't fill their own teams, girls can join boys' teams  
under provisions of the federal government's Title IX equal 
opportunity provisions for athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	That's Miranda's experience. She's on Stanford's men's team, but  
she wrestles women in national and international competition. It's 
all the same to her. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I walk onto the mat, I feel no connection to my gender,''  
Miranda said. ``I transform not only into a competitor but a 
wrestler.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for criticism that there could be something sexual in boys  
and girls grappling on a mat, Miranda doesn't buy it. ``I've never 
heard of a boy being turned on or being uncomfortable,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	If a male opponent feels uncomfortable wrestling a female,  
that's his problem, Miranda believes. 
</P>
<P>
	She knows some do. At Redwood Junior High in Saratoga, Calif.,  
``nobody told me not to be there, so it was a generally positive 
experience,'' she said. At Saratoga High, there was more 
``male-female politicking -- I don't want to say harassment,'' she 
said. ``But I was captain of my high school team by the time I was 
done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some junior high boys defaulted rather than wrestle her, Miranda  
recalled. ``Boys just do not want to lose to a girl,'' she said. By 
college, it's less of a factor -- and at Stanford, it's no factor at 
all, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea that boys would default rather than wrestle a girl  
angers Donna Lopiano, executive director of the Women's Sports 
Foundation in East Meadow, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think boys should be allowed to do it,'' she said.  
``The coach should say, `We are wrestling every athlete on that 
team. You either wrestle or you are not on the team.''' 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, the sport probably will grow to the point at which  
many girls' teams can be fielded, Lopiano said. 
</P>
<P>
	Girls who wrestle should be on female teams, said Walter  
Sargent, athletic director of Brookline, Mass., public schools, 
where the high school has a girls' team. 
</P>
<P>
	Girls should not wrestle boys, even when they can under Title  
IX, because it's bad for the girls, Sargent said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our kids say they get the opportunity to be offensive and  
aggressive, and not be in a defensive posture, as they would be 
against boys, who are stronger and bigger,'' Sargent said. And by 
not offering a girls' team, schools limit girls' participation to 
those girls who will wrestle boys, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Miranda disagrees. ``I don't see why a coach would make a  
judgment for the female population,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
