<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former King Congregation Moves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Members of the historic church once led by the  
Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., his father and his grandfather moved 
Sunday to a new, $8 million sanctuary across the street. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of members and visitors filled the wooden pews of the  
small, Ebenezer Baptist Church for a brief closing service where 
the congregation prayed and reflected on the church's 76-year 
history before marching over to the new 1,800-seat structure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have mixed emotions,'' said Christine King Ferris, King's  
sister, as she walked toward the new building. ``I will always have 
an affinity for Ebenezer. That was where I was baptized, where I 
was married and where my mother was killed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Singing ``We're Marching to Zion,'' and led by children, the  
congregation marched over to the fan-shaped building where church 
leaders cut the yellow ribbons on the doors of the new sanctuary. 
</P>
<P>
	The congregation had long since outgrown the old, 750-seat  
building, whose history has been marked with both triumph and 
tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1960s, Ebenezer served as the spiritual headquarters  
for the civil rights movement. Both King, his father and 
grandfather once preached from Ebenezer's pulpit, and it's where 
the slain civil rights leader's funeral was held in 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	Tragedy struck again in 1974 when King's mother, Alberta King,  
was gunned down while playing ``The Lord's Prayer'' on the organ. 
At the close of Sunday's service, the new church's organ was 
dedicated in her memory. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither King's widow, Coretta Scott King, nor any of his  
children were at Sunday's service. 
</P>
<P>
	For decades, Ebenezer has anchored the surrounding area known as  
``Sweet Auburn,'' once a center of black business that has since 
fallen on hard times. The neighborhood is where King grew up and is 
buried. 
</P>
<P>
	Political and social action will remain a focus of the new  
church's activity, said the Rev. Joseph Roberts Jr., pastor since 
1975. 
</P>
<P>
	``The mandate from Dr. King is still very much ours,'' Roberts  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	With its faded red brick facade, cracked ceiling and creaky  
floors, Ebenezer stands in stark contrast to the Afrocentric 
architectural of the New Horizon Sanctuary with its modern look and 
towering windows. 
</P>
<P>
	The new building can accommodate both a 150-member choir and  
1,800 in its oak pews, all of which were filled during Sunday's 
first worship service. 
</P>
<P>
	For Jethro English, an 86-year-old deacon who joined Ebenezer in  
1925, the old church holds many precious memories. As a young boy, 
he was baptized there and it's where he and his wife of 61 years 
were married by Martin Luther King Sr. He was a pallbearer at 
King's funeral and was sitting in the choir when Mrs. King was 
slain. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are so many precious memories there,'' English said.  
``I've seen the tragedies and I've seen the victories.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
