<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed. Health Tax Breaks Cost $111B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It cost the federal government $111.2 billion  
last year to give employers and their workers tax breaks to buy 
health insurance, a new study reports. Most of the money was spent 
on families earning more than $50,000 annually. 
</P>
<P>
	The study being published Monday in the journal Health Affairs  
highlights the contradictions in federal tax policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies do not have to pay taxes on money spent on workers'  
health insurance, and many employees do not have to pay taxes on 
their share of premiums. But Americans who pay for insurance out of 
their own pockets get no such break. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, 68.7 percent of the tax dollars lost because of these  
provisions benefited families earning more than $50,000 per year -- 
only about 36 percent of the population, the study found. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, 23.6 percent of the benefit went to families earning  
more than $100,000. 
</P>
<P>
	A disproportionate share of the tax benefit goes to wealthier  
families because higher-income workers are most likely to have 
health insurance, the authors explained. Also, families with higher 
incomes have higher tax rates, meaning a tax break for them costs 
the government more than a tax break for a lower-income worker 
would. 
</P>
<P>
	The study's authors questioned the spending.  
</P>
<P>
	``With more than 43 million uninsured persons in the United  
States, it is important to ask ourselves whether it is appropriate 
that 68.7 percent of the federal health benefits tax expenditures 
are going to 36 percent of the population with the highest 
incomes,'' said co-author John Sheils, vice president of the Lewin 
Group, a consulting firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The study also found that in 1998, total spending on  
employer-sponsored health coverage reached $302.6 billion. Of this, 
employers paid 83.4 percent with employees picking up the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax break for health insurance is a remnant of World War II,  
when the government encouraged companies to offer their workers 
health benefits in lieu of increased wages. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts note that this system is not necessarily the best for  
the health system as a whole. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies are encouraged to buy expensive health packages  
because money spent for health insurance is not taxed and therefore 
goes further than money spent on wages. The best health packages 
have low co-payments and low deductibles, making it cheaper for 
employees to use their insurance -- but driving up overall health 
care usage and spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., chairman of the House Ways and  
Means' health subcommittee, is working on a plan to restructure the 
health insurance tax system. He does not expect it to move through 
Congress soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
