<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies' Wright Finally Healthy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- At 6-foot-5 and 220 pounds, Jamey Wright  
has broad shoulders capable of carrying the weight of lofty 
expectations that accompany a former No. 1 draft pick. 
</P>
<P>
	After 2 1/2 years of gaining on-the-job experience with the  
Colorado Rockies, it's a burden he's ready to unload. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't use the he's-still-young excuse anymore,'' Wright  
said Sunday after throwing two scoreless innings against the San 
Francisco Giants. ``It's time to go out and prove I belong here. 
It's time to get up there in the win column and start proving 
myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wright, 24, Colorado's first-round draft choice in 1993, has had  
mixed results since allowing one hit in six innings in his major 
league debut on July 3, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The midseason callup completed a remarkable rise from Double-A  
in a three-month span, but injuries and inconsistency have impeded 
his progress in the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there'll be improvement this year,'' Rockies manager  
Jim Leyland said. ``I just don't want him to worry about taking 10 
steps up the ladder. Just take a couple more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A knee injury knocked Wright down a rung in 1996. He tore  
cartilage in his right knee while sliding into second base on his 
first major league hit and has had three surgeries since. 
</P>
<P>
	A collarbone injury shortened his season again in 1997, but he  
was able to pitch 200 innings for the first time last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright, who is 21-30 with a 5.71 ERA in his career, said he  
feels stronger this spring than he has since 1996. He likely will 
pitch third or fifth in Colorado's starting rotation with Darryl 
Kile, Pedro Astacio, Brian Bohanon and John Thomson. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jamey Wright has a real high ceiling,'' Leyland said. ``You  
have to let that play itself out rather than try to push it. I 
don't want to put too much on him, that this is the year he breaks 
through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As is wont for a blossoming 24-year-old, Wright has a youthful  
exuberance that tends to override patience. 
</P>
<P>
	He has junked his once hard-breaking slider in favor of a  
still-developing curveball he picked up last year from Kile. Wright 
also is working on decreasing the speed of his changeup to 
complement a fastball in the mid-90s. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've thrown three pitches forever and ever, and I've gotten to  
this level,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of winds gusting to 45 mph, Wright stayed primarily with  
his fastball Sunday. It was effective as he gave up a walk, a 
single and struck out a hitter in his 27-pitch spring debut. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't throw as many offspeed pitches as I would have liked  
to,'' he said. ``You're not going to be able to overpower guys with 
fastballs during the season. It's a lot easier to do it in the 
first part of spring training when they're not used to seeing 
them.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
