<DOCNO> APW19990307.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 16:13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Pushes Front-Runner Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- George W. Bush surrounded himself Sunday  
with a diverse group of high-profile Republicans to formally open 
the flirtation stage of his 2000 presidential campaign, furthering 
an unconventional strategy mapped out months ago to make him the 
GOP front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	Dropping nearly all pretense of indecision, the Texas governor  
unveiled his presidential exploratory committee by suggesting he 
will seek the White House unless ``there is a huge yawn'' from 
voters and donors when he starts traveling outside Texas in June. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing that would change my mind is if we got out there  
and just heard a loud thud,'' Bush said in a news conference 
attended by dozens of media organizations from around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	His 10-member exploratory committee includes three women, one of  
them black, one Hispanic man and one black man. Former Secretary of 
State George Shultz, GOP chairman Haley Barbour, Rep. J.C. Watts 
Jr. of Oklahoma and five other congressional Republicans give a 
Washington flavor to the group. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who answered one quesiton in Spanish, promised a more  
inclusive GOP that ``makes sure no one gets left behind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement gives shape to a field of at least 10  
Republicans. Lamar Alexander officially enters the campaign Tuesday 
and former American Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole will take 
the same baby step as Bush, forming her exploratory committee 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, a former Tennessee governor, said the strong showings  
by Bush and Dole in polls could be fleeting. Bush, son of former 
President George Bush, and Dole, wife of 1996 GOP nominee Bob Dole, 
benefit from name recognition, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pretty soon it will come on down back to earth,'' Alexander  
said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet The Press.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, 52, has held elective office just four years and seven  
weeks. He has not raised a dime as a presidential candidate. He has 
not trudged through the snows of Iowa and New Hampshire, begging 
for votes on the chicken-and-peas circuit with fellow contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet he is nurturing an aura of inevitability, leading in polls  
over the most likely Democratic nominee, Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican lawmakers from 14 states have urged Bush to run, with  
more to follow. At least 80 congressional Republicans have pledged 
support. And 16 Republican governors, a majority of the 31 GOP 
state executives, have signed up. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, running a front-porch campaign in the mold of William  
McKinley in 1896, has welcomed dozens of lawmakers, donors, 
businessman and operatives on pilgrimages to Austin. 
</P>
<P>
	This Bush bandwagon was built with tools he inherited, including  
his father's name, his state's political pull and his party's 
problems. But it also is the result of careful planning to maximize 
his luck. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of it is that Republicans really want to win this time.  
Part of it is buyers' remorse with President Clinton. Part of it is 
the resurgence of his dad's image. Part of it is his brother 
(Florida Gov. Jeb Bush) -- that two-brother thing works. Part of it 
is Texas -- there is a real panache about the state,'' said Ron 
Kaufman, White House political director for President Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	The blueprints were made months before the 1996 campaign, when  
the Bush team designed a re-election strategy that could blend 
seamlessly into a presidential bid. Bush was not certain he wanted 
to run for president, but certainly wanted the option open. 
</P>
<P>
	He won re-election in a landslide, securing unprecedented  
support from women, independents and minorities. The results 
impressed Republicans trying to broaden the party's appeal beyond 
anti-tax, anti-abortion, anti-Clinton activists. 
</P>
<P>
	``Republicans see him as a winner, and they're tired of  
losing,'' said Connecticut Gov. John Rowland, a Bush backer. 
</P>
<P>
	Consultant Karl Rove of Austin discretely organized the  
pilgrimages, lined up endorsements and urged operatives to await 
Bush's decision before jumping to early-organizing rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	While the hard work played out behind the scenes, Bush coyly and  
very publicly toyed with the notion of running for president, 
stoking the embers of interest without setting himself ablaze. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor orchestrated much of the hype, though ``it was very  
subtle,'' Rowland said. ``It didn't just fall in his lap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His announcement Sunday marks the beginning of tougher times for  
Bush, as he starts dealing with the hard issues of a campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got to pace himself,'' warned Rowland. ``We've all seen  
... front-runners flame out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush read a brief opening statement off a TelePrompTer and  
smoothly fielded most of the questions Sunday. He wavered when 
pressed for his views on abortion, saying the party should adopt a 
``pro-life tenor'' and calling a question about first-trimester 
abortions ``hypothetical.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rivals such as Steve Forbes who are courting conservatives will  
scrutinize Bush's every move. In a letter of support for Forbes 
released Sunday by conservatives L. Brent Bozell III, Richard 
Viguerie and Morton Blackwell, Bush is obliquely criticized as part 
of the ``Gore-lite'' element of the GOP. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also declined to give details about his positions on  
Kosovo, tax cuts and what he promised would be an ``economic 
stimulus'' package. Specifics will come after the Texas legislature 
adjourns in May, he said. Indeed, he offered little beyond what he 
told Texas reporters last Tuesday, though he sounded more certain 
about his candidacy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
