<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hornets Coach Dave Cowens Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) -- Dave Cowens resigned as coach of the  
Charlotte Hornets on Sunday, unhappy with being one of the NBA's 
lowest-paid coaches after leading the team to unprecedented success 
in his first two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowens informed the players of his decision before practice  
Sunday, then left the training facility. General Manager Bob Bass 
announced at an evening news conference that Cowens had submitted a 
letter of resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	The team did not announce an immediate successor, but the  
players were told it will be assistant Paul Silas, who played with 
Cowens for the Boston Celtics in the 1970s. Bass said the 
announcement of the interim coach would be made on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowens' departure is the latest blow to what was already the  
most difficult of the franchise's 11 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been one thing after another around here this year,''  
point guard B.J. Armstrong said, shaking his head, as he stood in 
the cold night air after the team held what was described as a 
somber practice following Cowens' announcement. ``You have a 
decision to make. Either you come together or you go into 
disarray.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Owner George Shinn has been accused of unwanted sexual conduct  
by three women, and fans are calling for him to either start paying 
the top dollars needed to keep good talent or sell the team. 
Injuries have sidelined Charlotte's top two players, and one of 
them, Glen Rice, is reportedly about to be traded to the Los 
Angeles Lakers. The team has struggled to a 4-11 record, and 
attendance has plummeted for a franchise that used to consistently 
be among the NBA's leader in sellout crowds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this franchise is going through mental fatigue,''  
forward Chuck Person said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowens walked into Bass' office late Sunday afternoon and told  
him he was leaving. Bass described the reasons as ``irreconcilable 
differences'' but refused to elaborate. Silas said he tried to talk 
Cowens out of resigning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody's ever prepared for something like this,'' Bass said.  
</P>
<P>
	Cowens, the only coach to lead the Hornets to consecutive 50-win  
seasons (54-28 in 1996-97, 51-31 in 1997-98), signed a 3-year, 
$1.89 million contract in May 1996. The contract called for him to 
get salaries of $575,000 his first year, $625,000 last year and 
$675,000 this season. 
</P>
<P>
	When Cowens went to Shinn last season and said he felt he should  
receive the NBA average of about $1.3 million, the Hornets offered 
him a four-year, $5.2 million extension. But Shinn reportedly 
withdrew the offer in February 1998 because he didn't feel Cowens 
was being appreciative enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowens went public with complaints about his salary late last  
month as the team struggled to get out of the gate during the 
lockout-shortened season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hornets are operating without top scorer Rice, who underwent  
elbow surgery before the season began. Leading rebounder Anthony 
Mason also underwent arm surgery and is out for the entire season. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team has taken a lot of hits already this year,'' Bass  
said. ``We've got 60 days left and hopefully we'll be able to make 
some progress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After practice, many of the players refused to comment, but  
starting guard Bobby Phills said Cowens' meeting with the players 
was an emotional one. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was very distraught,'' Phills said. ``Deep down, maybe it's  
something he didn't feel as though he wanted to do. But it's 
something he may have felt was best for his family and for 
himself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bass said the Hornets have no plans to bring in someone from  
outside the organization to coach the team, at least not between 
now and the end of this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Silas would be a sensible choice because he is the only one of  
the team's current assistants with previous NBA head coaching 
experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a difficult position to be in,'' Silas said. ``If it  
happens, I would have wanted it to happen differently.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong and teammate J.R. Reid said Silas will coach for the  
remainder of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Silas and Cowens won NBA championships together with the Celtics  
in 1974 and 1976. During his 16-year playing career, Silas played 
for St. Louis, Atlanta, Phoenix, Boston, Denver and Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him there's just two more months left in the season,  
but his mind was made up,'' Silas said of his attempt to convince 
Cowens to change his mind. ``At this point in the season, it's just 
shocking. That's the only word I can use.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silas coached the San Diego Clippers from 1980-83. All three of  
those teams had losing records. He interviewed last summer for 
head-coaching vacancies in Chicago, Sacramento and Seattle but 
didn't get any of the three jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a difficult position to be in,'' he said as he left  
the team's training center Sunday night, five hours after Cowens 
quit. ``But if you're called upon, then I think you have to accept 
it for the good of the organization, for the good of the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fans have called on Shinn to sell the Hornets for the good of  
the team, but club officials said late last week the team was not 
for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	``From management on down, I think you have to keep some things  
in the inner circle, and obviously we've shown an inability to,'' 
Person said. ``We're washing our dirty laundry outside in the cold 
on the old washboards, instead of keeping it inside where it's nice 
and cozy and there's a washer and dryer. Who knows what's going to 
come of this.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
