<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olajuwon Meets With Dying Boy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- A 4-year-old boy dying of brain cancer got  
a rare treat Sunday -- meeting the Houston Rockets star for whom he 
is named. 
</P>
<P>
	Olajuwon Wells, who has tumors in his brain and spine, seemed  
stunned when Rockets center Hakeem Olajuwon walked up to the boy 
and his family outside the visitors' locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy frowned for pictures with the 7-foot future Hall of  
Famer, but then brightened up and smiled after the player went back 
into the locker room to get ready for a game with the Portland 
Trail Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We show him who Hakeem is on the TV all the time,'' said  
Wells' mother, Clarissa Wells. ``But I don't think he realized who 
he was until he saw him for real just now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Wells and her husband, Cornell, named their son Olajuwon  
because of their devotion to the Rockets. They had never seen an 
NBA player, or a game, in person until Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a great player. I love the way he plays,'' Mrs. Wells  
said, trembling and tearing up after meeting Olajuwon. ``And that 
name just got to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked when his son's birthday was, Cornell, a Portland  
construction worker, said: ``Oct. 21, 1994 -- the Rockets repeated 
that year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The boy was diagnosed with cancer last month. His tumors are  
inoperable and has a life expectancy of about two years, said his 
doctor, Legacy Emanuel Hosptial pediatric neurosurgeon Monica 
Wehby. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a fighter,'' Cornell Wells said. ``He told me himself,  
Daddy, I'm going to fight this all the way to the end. And I 
believe that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
