<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Fans Rejoice at Orioles News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Amid the clanging steel drums, trumpet blares and  
impassioned screams of a playoff game, Cuban baseball fans 
responded with joy Sunday upon learning that the Baltimore Orioles 
will play the national team here on March 28. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that they do come,'' Stanley Hynds, a 25-year-old  
barber, shouted above the crowd as he gyrated his hips in an 
improvised celebration dance. ``It will be a pleasure for us to see 
them and to see them lose right here in this stadium!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Major league baseball will return to Cuba for the first time in  
40 years with the deal completed Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement was made in the United States, but the word  
circulated among the 40,000 fans who crowded into the 
Latinoamericano Stadium Sunday afternoon for the playoff between 
the two hometown favorites: the Industriales and La Habana. The 
playoff series began last week. 
</P>
<P>
	While the U.S. baseball season has not yet started, the regular  
Cuban season begins in November and ends in April. 
</P>
<P>
	``We agree with the idea of their coming to our country to  
play,'' said Marina Ruiz Garnemedia, the director of a children's 
performance group, whose members banged on metal percussion 
instruments, danced the rumba and chanted support for their 
favorite team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Win Industriales! Win!' shouted the girls in matching  
turquoise skirts and cropped tops and boys with multi-colored shirt 
sleeves. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will be a very human, very personal contact between the  
people of our two countries,'' Ruiz, 45, said with a broad grin. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cuban team is to play a return exhibition game at Camden  
Yards. The second game will be played either just before Baltimore 
starts the regular season April 5 or on an off day during the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement came after two months of negotiations between the  
State Department, Cuban government, commissioner's office, the 
Orioles and the players' association. 
</P>
<P>
	Major league baseball teams used to visit Cuba regularly, but  
the last were the Cincinnati Reds and Los Angeles Dodgers, who 
played exhibition games there in March 1959, about 2 1/2 months after 
Fidel Castro's revolution ousted dictator Fulgencio Batista on New 
Year's Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Fresneda, 66, a construction worker, said he remembers  
that game, as well as the games that Cuba's Sugar Kings played here 
against Triple A teams from the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``I come to every game at this stadium,'' said Fresneda. ``And  
you can be sure that I'll come here for the Orioles game, too.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
