<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palmeiro Out at Least a Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Texas Rangers first baseman Rafael  
Palmeiro had his second knee operation within a month on Sunday and 
will be sidelined 4-to-6 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been told there's a chance he'll be ready for opening  
day,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``I don't know how 
accurate that is but I'm going to go on that. I'm just trying to 
make plans for the last few days knowing that this would be a 
possibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The latest surgery was to repair torn cartilage in his right  
knee. Palmeiro, who played with the Rangers from 1989-93 before 
re-signing as a free agent during the offseason, also had surgery 
Feb. 10 to repair another injury on the same knee. 
</P>
<P>
	He was working out with the club and had been expected to return  
by the end of the week, but reinjured his knee while jogging 
Thursday. Dr. John Conway operated on the knee Sunday at Fort 
Worth, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas general manager Doug Melvin said there is an outside  
chance Palmeiro could be ready for opening day, ``but realistically 
we'll have to look at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers, flush with talent at first base going into spring  
training, suddenly are scrambling to fill the position. 
Outfielder/first baseman Mike Simms also is out for up to a month 
with a partially torn left Achilles' tendon. Designated hitter Lee 
Stevens will fill in. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I just have to get us by out there until these guys  
get back,'' Stevens said. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmeiro, 34, has appeared in 1,368 games in the '90s, second to  
Cal Ripken Jr. He has not missed more than three games in a season 
since 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
