<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Albanians Expected To Sign Kosovo Deal  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Kosovo's Albanian leaders later today are expected  
to sign a peace plan to give them autonomy -- a pledge that would 
intensify pressure on the Serbs to sign the agreement or face NATO 
airstrikes. Former Sen. Bob Dole, who negotiated the agreement at 
the request of President Clinton, said yesterday that he was 
confident Kosovo's Albanians would follow through. So far, the 
Serbs have accepted most of the political aspects of the peace plan 
to give broad self-rule to Kosovo for the next three years; the 
province's future would be decided later. 

</P>
<P>
	Another Global Balloon Quest Fails  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Two British balloonists were safely rescued earlier  
today after ditching into the Pacific near Japan, ending their 
attempt to be the first to circumnavigate the globe in a hot-air 
balloon. The British Cable and Wireless balloon landed 200 miles 
off the coast of central Japan, according to an official from 
Japan's Maritime Safety Agency. Pilots Andy Elson and Colin Prescot 
were rescued by a Japanese Air Self-Defense Force helicopter. 

</P>
<P>
	Back Injury Cancels First Lady Trip  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton will not accompany the  
president on a four-day goodwill tour of Central America this week 
because of a recurring back injury, the first lady's spokeswoman 
said today. Mrs. Clinton aggravated a previously injured back 
muscle while on a skiing vacation in Utah with her President 
Clinton and their daughter, Chelsea, said spokeswoman Marsha Berry. 

</P>
<P>
	Saudi Arabia To Buy U.S. Missiles  
</P>
<P>
	RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- The United States today agreed to  
sell Saudi Arabia sophisticated missiles, according to a U.S. 
defense official. Secretary of Defense William Cohen reached the 
agreement for the hardware in a meeting with Saudi Prince Sultan. 
The Advanced Medium-Range Air-to-Air Missiles will likely be used 
on F-16 fighter jets and are a high priority given the increasingly 
aggressive tactics being employed by Iraqi air forces. No purchase 
price for the missiles was disclosed 

</P>
<P>
	Indian Military Plane Crash Kills 21  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- An Indian air force transport plane  
crashed near a huge township today and exploded in a ball of fire 
in a cluster of bricklayers' huts, killing 21 people, officials 
said. The Russian-built AN-32 aircraft suddenly veered as it 
prepared to land, clipped a brick boundary wall and vaulted into a 
massive drinking water reservoir, flattening dozens of brick huts 
belonging to workers building water storage tanks, witnesses said. 
The dead included 18 people in the plane and three in the huts. 

