<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lott: Banana Fight Threatens WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The showdown over bananas between the United  
States and Europe has put the future of the World Trade 
Organization at risk, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Europeans don't start dealing with us more honestly in  
complying with WTO decisions, I don't know that WTO is going to 
exist or amount to anything,'' Lott, R-Miss., said on ``Fox News 
Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO has become the battleground for a dispute between the  
United States and the European Union over European restrictions on 
imports of Central and Latin American bananas. The WTO ruled 
against the Europeans in 1997. But the United States, saying the EU 
had not adequately redressed the issue, announced plans to impose 
$520 million in retaliatory tariffs on European goods. 
</P>
<P>
	The 133-nation WTO, set up in 1995, meets in emergency session  
Monday to hear the EU's complaint that the U.S. sanctions are 
illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The WTO made a decision on bananas. The Europeans have stiffed  
us,'' Lott said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he is a free trader but believes that stiff penalties  
should be imposed on any country that dumps goods in this country 
or otherwise practices unfair trade. Lott said he is against 
letting China, which has had a stormy trade relationship with the 
United States, join the WTO. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration is pushing the case because American  
companies, including Chiquita Brands International Inc. and Dole 
Food Co., grow their bananas mostly in Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Commerce Committee Chairman and GOP presidential hopeful  
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said he worries about protectionist 
sentiments evident within the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look, I care about bananas. My kids eat them every day. But  
I'm not sure that's a reason for us to escalate into a trade war 
here,'' he said, also on Fox. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain said he was glad TV commentator Pat Buchanan, a strong  
proponent of protecting U.S. industries, is running for president 
again so the issue of free trade could be debated. ``I'm deeply 
concerned about this rise in protectionism and isolationism,'' 
McCain said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
