<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Precocity Wins New Orleans Handicap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Precocity upset 1998 Kentucky Derby and  
Preakness Stakes winner Real Quiet and a small field to win by a 
half-length Sunday in the $500,000 New Orleans Handicap at the Fair 
Grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Eddie Martin Jr., Precocity made his move from the  
fifth position in a six-horse field midway through the final turn. 
When the horses straightened out for home, the 5-year-old 
maneuvered outside Take Note of Me, Allen's Oop and Real Quiet. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-to-2 second choice in the betting inched past second-place  
Real Quiet in the final strides to claim the $322,121 winner's 
share of the purse in the time of 1:49. 
</P>
<P>
	Real Quiet's first start since losing the 1998 Belmont Stakes by  
a nose to Victory Gallop was impressive. The favorite ran second 
among a cluster of three horses ahead of the small field through a 
1 1/8 miles. But when jockey Kent Desormeaux called upon him to fire 
at the end, the 1998 Eclipse Award winning 3-year-old did not 
respond to Precocity's charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen's Oop finished third.  
</P>
<P>
	Since Real Quiet's inactivity because of a slight injury in the  
Belmont Stakes, Precocity had run seven times. His last outing was 
an easy victory in the Whirlaway Stakes at the Fairgrounds on Feb. 
14. In that race, he came from fourth place to catch the leaders 
nearly in identical style. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory on the fast track increased Precocity's earnings for  
owner John Franks to $1,667,462. He finished second to Phantom On 
Tour in the 1998 New Orleans Handicap. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner, bought privately from Real Quiet's trainer Bob  
Baffert, paid $7.60, $2.60 and $2.10. 
</P>
<P>
	Real Quiet paid $2.40 and $2.10. Allen's Oop paid $2.10.  
</P>
</TEXT>
