<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paper: More Sports Harassment Suits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- More men are coaching women's teams -- and  
getting accused of sexual harassment, The New York Times reported 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	With the increase in women's sports since the enactment of Title  
IX, the percentage of women coaching female teams has declined from 
90 percent in 1972 to 47 percent, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	While few statistics are available, the Times interviewed about  
50 athletes, parents, coaches, administrators and researchers. 
Lawsuits against North Carolina soccer coach Anson Dorrance, the 
former coach of the U.S. national team, and Syracuse tennis coach 
Jesse Dwire have highlighted the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a big problem out there,'' Don Sabo, a sociology  
professor at D'Youville College in Buffalo, told the Times. ``It's 
all about emotions, about trust, and about the body.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Joel Fish, director of the Center for Sport Psychology in  
Philadelphia, added: ``The whole issue of sexual harassment within 
athletics, of coaches trying to understand the boundaries of what's 
right and wrong, of when to yell and when to pat her on the back, 
of whether or not to hug, is still being defined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Debbie Keller, a U.S. national team player and a former college  
player of the year, has accused Dorrance of inappropriate behavior 
that included uninvited sexual comments. 
</P>
<P>
	Melissa Jennings has accused Dorrance, who has led North  
Carolina to 15 NCAA titles and the United States to a Women's World 
Cup championship, of creating a hostile environment for her before 
cutting her from the team. Dorrance has denied the allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	Dwire, a 20-year veteran at Syracuse, was accused of massaging,  
fondling and propositioning two scholarship tennis players, Kirsten 
Ericson and Dacia Kornechuk, in a suit scheduled for trial March 29 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit accuses the school of retaliating against the players  
after they pursued a complaint through the university's grievance 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	A university panel recommended a two-year ban of Dwire in 1997,  
finding he had violated policies regarding sexual harassment and 
discrimination. However, the penalty was reduced to a three-month 
suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	A Syracuse spokesman said neither Dwire nor any of the dozen  
university administrators named in the suit would comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
