<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Closing in on 10,000 Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Suddenly, 10,000 is looking like a possibility  
again. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average had its biggest two-day point  
gain ever this past week, putting the blue chips at a new closing 
high of 9,736.08, and restarting talk about the next big milestone 
for the stock market's most widely-followed barometer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Short-term, it certainly looks like the market wants to make a  
run for 10,000,'' said A. Marshall Acuff, Jr., equity strategist at 
Salomon Smith Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow's achievement's were remarkable. It rose 268.68 points  
Friday after a 191.52 point surge Thursday, for a total of 460 
points. The rally resuscitated a bull market that had been squeezed 
almost lifeless in recent weeks by higher interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The impetus for Wall Street's surge was twofold.  
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, IBM announced it had agreed to supply Dell Computer  
with $16 billion worth of parts over seven years. The deal 
supported assertions that technology stocks, the undisputed leader 
in the market's advance since last fall, still have some life. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, on Friday, the Labor Department reported that the economy  
is producing new jobs without feeding inflation. Analysts said the 
report gave the Federal Reserve no reason to raise rates to cool 
the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The dynamics of the rally augured well for the market. Wall  
Street's leadership broadened from just technology and medical 
stocks, which have carried the market's water for some time, to 
include financial, retail, energy, even economically sensitive 
manufacturing issues. 
</P>
<P>
	That trend helps to raise optimism about the market's future.  
Thom Brown, market strategist at Rutherford, Brown &AMP; Catherwood in 
Philadelphia, said that, ``in three years' time, you could easily 
see Dow 13,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But there are still causes for concern. Although angst about  
short-term interest rates lessened with Friday's economic report, 
long-term interest rates have gone up, closing Friday at just under 
5.6 percent after starting the year at 5.51 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	And consumer credit is growing at a very strong 13.5 percent  
annual rate, the Federal Reserve reported Friday. That does raise 
the possibility that the Fed, hoping to stave off an overheating 
economy, might decide to tighten credit after all. 
</P>
<P>
	A Fed tightening would be deadly for the bull market, which owes  
its spectacular gains and longevity to low interest rates that keep 
consumers and corporations borrowing, spending, and stoking 
corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, the stock market still has to justify extraordinarily  
high valuations, which only got higher this past week. Stocks in 
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 composite were selling at an unheard-of 
29 times 1999 earnings, and that was before Friday's rally. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm skeptical of the valuation levels that I see,'' Brown  
said. ``They're historically so far above anything we've been used 
to in the past, and that in and of itself makes professional market 
observers wary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow's advance gave it a gain of 429.50 for the week. The  
industrials are up 6 percent since the year began. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Nasdaq composite index rose 44.22 to 2,337.11,  
gaining 49.08 for the week. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 composite 
advanced 28.83 to 1,275.47, up 37.14 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Stock Exchange's market index rose 12.39 to 603.14,  
up 16.68 for the week. The American Stock Exchange's composite 
index rose 8.89 to 707.41, up 9.12 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of mid-sized companies added 3.99 to  
398.01, up 5.76 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilshire 5000 index, which represents the combined market value  
of all NYSE, American and Nasdaq issues, ended the week at $11.6 
trillion, up $311 billion. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
