<DOCNO> APW19990307.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 20:11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Report: Kurds Down Copter, 20 Dead  
</P>
<P>
	DIYARBAKIR, Turkey (AP) -- Kurdish rebels claimed today they shot  
down an army helicopter, killing 20 Turkish soldiers, a Kurdish 
news agency reported. The German-based DEM reported that all aboard 
the helicopter died in the southeastern province of Hakkari. The 
rebels recently vowed that their fight for autonomy would escalate 
in defiance of the recent capture of their leader, Abdullah Ocalan. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Visit Central America  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton ventures empty-handed into  
hurricane-clobbered reaches of Central America this week as nearly 
$1 billion in aid is trapped on Capitol Hill by unrelated, partisan 
disputes. The message of solidarity with America's neighbors that 
he will trumpet during his trip to Nicaragua, El Salvador, 
Guatemala and Honduras is aimed as much at Congress as at the 
people rebuilding the region's roads, homes and schools in the 
aftermath of last fall's Hurricane Mitch. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Announces 2000 Committee  
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Dropping nearly all pretense of indecision,  
Gov. George W. Bush unveiled his presidential exploratory committee 
today by suggesting he will seek the White House unless ``there is 
a huge yawn'' from voters and donors when he starts traveling in 
June. Bush surrounded himself with a diverse group of high-profile 
Republicans to make his announcement, furthering an unconventional 
strategy mapped out months ago to make him the GOP front-runner for 
the nomination. Bush leads in polls over the most likely Democratic 
nominee, Vice President Al Gore. 

</P>
<P>
	Benigni, Paltrow Win SAG Awards  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- An exuberant Roberto Benigni captured a lead  
actor prize for ``Life is Beautiful'' and Gwyneth Paltrow took home 
an actress award that she dedicated to her mother at the Screen 
Actors Guild awards tonight. Robert Duvall and Kathy Bates also 
received honors. Benigni's award was the biggest surprise of the 
night and suggested the best actor Oscar later this month is a 
toss-up. Paltrow was awarded for her role as the heiress who falls 
in love with a young William Shakespeare in ``Shakespeare in 
Love.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Gas Line Explodes in Michigan  
</P>
<P>
	PLAINWELL, Mich. (AP) -- A natural gas line ruptured today in a  
rural area north of Kalamazoo, causing an explosion that was felt 
for miles. There were no reports of injuries and the cause was 
unknown, according to Consumers Energy, a utility company. The 
explosion happened about 7:30 p.m. and the glow from the fire lit 
up the sky for two hours. The fire was out about three hours later, 
and utility workers were on the scene to isolate the line and 
pinpoint what caused the explosion. 

</P>
<P>
	Group Protests Pope's Visit to Iran  
</P>
<P>
	VATICAN CITY (AP) -- Italian police today asked a small group of  
protesters in St. Peter's Square to lower a banner that asked Pope 
John Paul II not to meet with Iran's president this week. President 
Mohammad Khatami will meet with the pope on Thursday during the 
first trip to the West by an Iranian president since the 1979 
Islamic revolution. 

</P>
<P>
	Director Stanley Kubrick Dies  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Stanley Kubrick, a visionary craftsman whose films  
-- including ``Dr. Strangelove'' and ``A Clockwork Orange'' -- 
reflected an often violent and despairing view of life, died today. 
He was 70. ``Stanley Kubrick was the grandmaster of filmmaking. He 
copied no one, while all of us were scrambling to imitate him,'' 
director Steven Spielberg said in a statement. Kubrick had been 
preparing for the midyear release of ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' his first 
film in 12 years. 

</P>
<P>
	Intel Now the Target of Antitrust  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It is now Intel's turn inside the antitrust  
courtroom. The microchip giant will take center stage Tuesday in an 
administrative law hearing at the FTC. The case carries high stakes 
that ultimately could affect prices, quality and innovation in 
computers millions of people now use. The central issue in the 
government's complaint is whether Intel holds a monopoly in the 
market for microprocessors, the ``brains'' of computers. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose Monday following a 5 percent  
rally in the market's main index Friday and a new record high on 
Wall Street. The Nikkei Stock Average gained 95.75 points in early 
trading. 

</P>
<P>
	NCAA Unveils Tournament Seedings  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- The Big Ten today tied the record with  
seven teams selected for the 64-team NCAA tournament. The 
Southeastern Conference grabbed most of the top spots, however, 
with one-fourth of the top 16 seeds. Top-ranked Duke, Michigan 
State, Auburn and Connecticut were named No. 1 seeds. In addition 
to regular-season and tournament champion Michigan State, the other 
Big Ten teams selected were Ohio State, Indiana, Iowa, Minnesota, 
Wisconsin and Purdue. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  
</P>
