<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How-To Bomb Guide Had Govt in Furor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Armed only with encyclopedia diagrams and a  
few college courses in physics, Howard Morland set out 20 years ago 
to discover the secret of the hydrogen bomb. 
</P>
<P>
	He came close, so close that the federal government fought to  
stop the Madison-based magazine The Progressive from publishing his 
free-lance article, ``The H-Bomb Secret: How We Got It, Why We're 
Telling It.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cold War was still on and federal officials were worried  
about the national security risk of letting the bomb secrets out of 
the bag. 
</P>
<P>
	After The Progressive refused a request that it censor the  
article itself, the government went to court. On March 9, 1979, it 
won a temporary restraining order under the 1954 Atomic Energy Act 
that delayed publication for six months. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said the article threatened ``grave, direct,  
immediate and irreparable harm to the national security of the 
United States,'' even though it conceded that individual components 
of the article, gleaned from public libraries and tours of nuclear 
facilities, were not restricted. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue might seem melodramatic in today's era of freewheeling  
information dissemination across the Internet, where people can 
easily access ``The Terrorist's Handbook'' or ``The Anarchist 
Cookbook'' on the World Wide Web. Several Web pages deal with 
making hydrogen or atomic bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	But The Progressive case was only the second in American history  
that temporarily upheld prior restraint of publication. The first 
involved the Nixon administration's attempt to stop newspapers from 
printing the Pentagon Papers, the classified study of U.S. 
involvement in Vietnam -- which the U.S. Supreme Court eventually 
allowed to be published. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been prior restraint cases since 1979, but none based  
on national security, said David Rudenstine, a law professor at 
Cardozo Law School in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Editors of The Progressive argued that none of the information  
in their article was really secret and that the piece would help 
demystify nuclear theory. 
</P>
<P>
	``We realized that by not breaking any laws, not getting any  
scientist drunk, not getting any government secrets, you could 
figure out the deepest, darkest secret that the government must 
surely have, such as how to build a hydrogen bomb,'' said Sam Day, 
The Progressive's managing editor at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Day, 72, still a writer in Madison, said the article didn't  
enable anyone to actually build a hydrogen bomb, since that costs 
``billions and billions of dollars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Progressive eventually prevailed, but by then the government  
had dropped its case because another publication had printed key 
bomb-making steps. 
</P>
<P>
	Morland says he pursued the article as a ``missionary or  
evangelist'' in the campaign to abolish nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``My motivation was a very strongly held belief that the entire  
human race ... had discovered that the creator had played a huge 
joke on us,'' Morland said in a telephone interview from his home 
in Arlington, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we got smart enough to figure out nuclear forces, would  
we be wise enough to handle that knowledge? It's a test and there 
is only one right answer: permanent abolition of nuclear weapons 
for all time,'' said Morland, 56. 
</P>
<P>
	The historical consequences of the Progressive case have been  
modest because it never reached the Supreme Court or challenged the 
boundaries of the Atomic Energy Act, but it did have implications 
for freedom of the press. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a significant victory for the magazine and a  
significant victory for the First Amendment,'' said Brady 
Williamson, a lawyer for The Progressive. ``Practically speaking, 
the government cannot prevent journalists from writing articles 
based on essentially accurate information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Publication didn't have any apparent impact on nuclear  
proliferation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It surely hasn't led to anyone reading his article and buying  
a book and then designing a hydrogen bomb. So it didn't do what 
people feared, giving someone who wanted to build a bomb the 
blueprint on how to do it,'' said Paul Leventhal, president of the 
Nuclear Control Institute, a nonprofit organization based in 
Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Leventhal adds: ``A nuclear bomb is within the reach of  
a determined group or an outlaw state who wants to get a hold of 
this material, and I think Howard (Morland) helped to draw 
attention to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Is there anything today Morland would balk at publishing?  
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that pops in my mind is if I knew how to combine the  
lethality of the AIDS virus with the transmissibility of the common 
cold,'' he said, ``I would not tell anybody that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990307.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 12:31:50 </DATE_TIME>
