<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Botha Wins 800m at World Indoors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAEBASHI, Japan (AP) -- When Johan Botha woke up sick, he knew he  
was ready to win -- and he did, over world record holder Wilson 
Kipketer in an upset at the World Indoor Track Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I woke up this morning I felt sick to my stomach and  
stiff all over, all the signs of nervousness,'' Botha said. ``But 
it's never good to feel too good before a race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, feeling as bad as he did, ``I knew I was going to do  
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The South African won the men's 800 meters in 1 minute, 45.47  
seconds, just edging out Kipketer, whose time was 1:45.49. Nico 
Motchebon, of Germany, took the bronze in 1:45.74. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's 800 offered an even bigger surprise.  
</P>
<P>
	Mozambique's Maria Mutola, a three-time indoor champion, lost  
her first race inside since 1992. She was second to Ludmila 
Formanova of the Czech Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	And she was so shocked she got sick, too. She was examined by  
doctors after the race, but quickly recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a world championships race. Anything can happen,'' she  
said later. ``It's one of those things. You never know who's going 
to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Formanova's time was 1:56.90, a championships' record and the  
second-fastest indoors ever. Mutola finished in 1:57.17. 
</P>
<P>
	Though both of the winners were underdogs, they have been having  
exceptionally good races lately. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's gold caps a sensational year for Botha, who has won all  
seven of his races. He also defeated Kipketer, who is coming off a 
six-month break, in the semifinal of the championships as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been winning all my races this year, so maybe I should  
have been the favorite,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he added, ``this is my first indoor season, and to come  
through and win the world championship is a dream come true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kipketer, who set the indoor world record of 1:42.67 last March,  
said he did his best. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm satisfied,'' he said. ``I gained something from it.''  
</P>
<P>
	Formanova, the European indoor champion, had also been unbeaten  
this winter, and going into the championships had the 
second-fastest time of the year, 1:58.78, after Mutola's 1:57.06. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before going to sleep last night I thought about whether  
Mutola could be beaten,'' she said. ``But I told myself, she's only 
human, just like me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
