<DOCNO> APW19990307.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 15:21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Half of Carjackings Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Just over half the nation's annual average of  
nearly 49,000 carjacking attempts are successful, and almost 
two-thirds of the incidents occur within five miles of the owner's 
home, the Justice Department reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporting on data for 1992 through 1996, the most recent  
available, the Bureau of Justice Statistics said that each year an 
average of 48,787 carjackings are tried, and 24,520, or 50.3 
percent, succeed. 
</P>
<P>
	Victims were injured in 23 percent of the completed carjackings  
but in only 10 percent of the unsuccessful ones. A weapon was used 
in 83 percent of the incidents. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said 84 percent of victims were not injured, but 4  
percent suffered serious injuries, such as gunshot or knife wounds, 
broken bones, internal injuries or loss of consciousness. The 
remainder had minor injuries like bruises or chipped teeth. Some 
incidents had more than one victim. 
</P>
<P>
	The bureau defined carjacking as a theft in which a vehicle was  
taken or attempted to be taken by force or threat of it. It counted 
only carjackings by strangers, not by acquaintances or relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	The bureau's survey had no data on murders during carjackings  
because the figures are estimates based on interviews during 
1992-1996 with 430,000 U.S. residents over age 12. Only survivors 
could be interviewed. 
</P>
<P>
	Using FBI data based on police reports, the bureau said  
strangers committed an average of 27 murders involving automobile 
theft each year during 1992-1996. ``These may have been 
carjackings,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 22 percent of carjackings occurred at or near the victim's  
home, but 65 percent were within five miles or less. The bureau 
offered no explanation, but law-enforcement and automobile club 
officials privately suggested that most cars spend most of their 
time within five miles of the owner's home. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty percent of the incidents occurred in open areas, such as  
on the street or near a bus, subway or train station or airport. 
Also, 20 percent were in parking lots or near stores, restaurants, 
gas stations and office buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	Carjackings were more successful in daylight hours, two of three  
times. At night, less than half the attempts succeeded. 
</P>
<P>
	A firearm was used in 70 percent of the successful incidents, 20  
percent of the unsuccessful ones. 
</P>
<P>
	No resistance was offered by 38 percent of the victims. The  
other 62 percent took some kind of action to defend themselves or 
their property. 
</P>
<P>
	The report showed 19 percent of victims attacked, chased or  
tried to catch the offender or threatened use of a weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-four percent of victims used nonconfrontational defenses  
like running away, calling for help or trying to attract attention. 
</P>
<P>
	The remainder used unspecified defenses.  
</P>
<P>
	The bureau said the data were not sufficient to analyze the  
impact of various self-defenses on either the rate of victim injury 
or the success rate of the carjacking attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	The bureau found that all the completed carjackings were  
reported to the police, but authorities were told about just 57 
percent of the attempted carjackings. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the bureau's second study of carjacking. A study five  
years ago found a somewhat lower annual average number of 
carjackings. 
</P>
<P>
	Those totals, however, cannot be compared with the current  
figures because, in the interim, the questions used in the 
interviews were altered to probe the carjacking issue more fully, 
bureau spokesman Stu Smith said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
