<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sweepstakes Industry Under Assault </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The sweepstakes ``performance review'' sent to  
Mr. R. Miller is marked ``personal &AMP; confidential'' and includes 
details on a $1 million drawing. 
</P>
<P>
	The material rates how well Miller did such things as filling  
out Publishers Clearing House entry forms and mailing them on time 
and how he can upgrade his status with the company by making 
purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	State regulators says people are being duped by such personal  
appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're getting you to buy because they make you believe that  
out of the millions and millions and millions of people who have 
sent in responses, that you have personally come to their 
attention,'' said Wisconsin Attorney General James Doyle. 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle's state is one of several suing sweepstakes houses over  
their mailings. 
</P>
<P>
	In Miller's case, he earned ``exceptional'' ratings in every  
category but one: ``Often takes advantage of our Unbeatable 
Deals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Commendable'' was his grade there. An attached note tells  
Miller he qualifies for an upcoming $1 million drawing, and can 
upgrade his status with the company by ordering ``by the 
deadline.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sweepstakes industry is under new scrutiny on several  
fronts, including Senate legislation that would affect companies 
such as Publishers Clearing House and American Family Publishers. 
</P>
<P>
	A bill sponsored by Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, would set fines  
up to $2 million for deceptive sales tactics and provide the first 
federal regulation targeting the sweepstakes industry. 
</P>
<P>
	A Senate committee plans hearings next week.  
</P>
<P>
	State regulators also are complaining sweepstakes companies  
target the elderly. Several states have sued the biggest 
sweepstakes houses, alleging a variety of deceptive practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys general from about half the country met in  
Indianapolis last month to look at mailings that seem to promise a 
far greater chance of winning if the consumer buys something. 
</P>
<P>
	Under federal law, no purchase is necessary to enter or win a  
sweepstakes, and industry representatives note there are 
disclaimers with the You May Already be a Winner promotions. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to give credit to the American people,'' said Bob  
Wientzen, president and CEO of the Direct Marketing Association, an 
industry group. ``They do know these sweepstakes use copy that 
might suggest they might be a winner in a very strong way, but they 
recognize that's just part of the sweepstakes offer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sweepstakes companies keep using high-test language in their  
mailings because it works, Wientzen said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They respond at higher levels when this sort of dream copy is  
written. Sweepstakes is very much about fantasy and dreaming you 
could win, and I think people enjoy them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The industry estimates 70 percent of households toss the  
mailings without entering a contest or buying any magazine 
subscriptions or other merchandise. 
</P>
<P>
	Of those who do return the envelope, about 75 percent decline to  
buy anything, said Christopher L. Irving, director of consumer 
affairs for Publishers Clearing House. 
</P>
<P>
	But those who do buy are targeted for additional mailings and  
additional offers, with what Wisconsin's Doyle calls the clear 
implication that more purchases means a better chance at winning a 
prize. 
</P>
<P>
	Wisconsin's suit singles out Publishers Clearing House, and  
Doyle points to a letter signed by Dorothy Addeo, the firm's 
contest manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``My boss dropped into my office the other day, sat down and  
sighed. What's the story with Norman G. Ziolkowski?'' the letter 
says, noting the name appears on the President's Club Member List, 
among other places, but not on the Winners List. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had my mission, Norman G. Ziolkowski. To make you a winner --  
and soon,'' the letter continues. Ziolkowski is guaranteed to win 
something if he responds to a forthcoming mailing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have alleged that the boss of the company never walked into  
Dorothy Addeo's office and sighed and mentioned this person by 
name,'' Doyle said. ``It's certainly a false and misleading 
statement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irving called the letter a ``dramatization'' of real  
conversations at the company. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that a frequent buyer gets more opportunities is not  
unusual. It's direct marketing, and there's certainly nothing wrong 
with that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
