<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Church Addresses Gay Elder Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A gay elder's election to the governing  
board of a Presbyterian church has been upheld by an ecclesiastical 
court, which rejected a challenge by members who said the man's 
homosexuality violates church law. 
</P>
<P>
	Wayne Osborne was welcomed with hugs and handshakes as he made  
his way down the center aisle of the First Presbyterian Church of 
Stamford just before the start of services Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, in a decision released Saturday, rejected a challenge  
by two church members who said Osborne's election violates a recent 
amendment to the Constitution of the Presbyterian Church that bans 
practicing homosexuals from holding church office. 
</P>
<P>
	Osborne said he was gratified by the decision, but still  
concerned about other gay church members who may also face 
resistance because of the new amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are still people under the weight of this,'' he said.  
``I think many gays and lesbians will find hope from this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Controversy at the church erupted last May after the 800-family  
congregation elected Osborne, 38, to serve on the governing board, 
known as a session. 
</P>
<P>
	He had previously been ordained as an elder and served on a  
session, but since then had begun to live openly as a homosexual. 
</P>
<P>
	Two members of the church filed a complaint. They said Osborne's  
lifestyle violated church doctrine and therefore prevented his 
installation on the session. 
</P>
<P>
	William Prey, a church adviser to the two complainants, said  
they are considering an appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
