<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox Hire Fisk To Assist GM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Carlton Fisk showed that time does heal  
bad feelings. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisk, who left Boston with bitterness after the 1980 season, was  
hired Sunday as a special assistant to Red Sox general manager Dan 
Duquette. He is expected to work with the club's minor league 
catchers and make appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was a long time ago that that happened,'' Fisk said.  
``The people that caused that situation are not here anymore. For 
me it's a fresh start, a new start. There are no parts of the prior 
regimes behind the doors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisk, the 1972 AL Rookie of the Year, is best remembered for his  
extra-inning homer off the left-field foul pole that won Game 6 of 
the 1975 World Series. The Reds came back to win the final game. 
</P>
<P>
	``The entire Red Sox family is extremely pleased that Carlton is  
rejoining the organization,'' Duquette said. ``This is something 
that we've been working on for some time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisk left the team, then-partly owned by Haywood Sullivan, after  
Boston failed to mail him a contract by the Dec. 20 deadline in 
1980, allowing him to become a free agent. He spent his final 13 
seasons with the Chicago White Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if I ever envisioned being back with this  
organization,'' Fisk said. ``I did envision being back in the game 
in some respect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisk hasn't said which hat he would wear if he is elected to the  
Hall of Fame. He fell 43 votes short this year, his first season of 
eligibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll cross that bridge when we get there,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
