<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky: I Betrayed Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky, in an interview with Time  
magazine, says she betrayed President Clinton by telling Linda 
Tripp and other friends about their affair. 
</P>
<P>
	``Only telling 10 people was being pretty discreet for me,'' she  
says in the Time edition appearing on newsstands Monday. ``I 
betrayed the president in that way. I didn't have the foresight to 
see what the possible ramifications of this could be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp, appearing Sunday on ABC's ``This Week,'' belittled  
Ms. Lewinsky's accounts of the affair, saying they have ``almost no 
bearing on reality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky, as in her interview with ABC's Barbara Walters  
aired last week and a new biography by British author Andrew 
Morton, tells Time that she ``didn't have the maturity to realize 
exactly how serious'' the fallout of her affair with Clinton would 
be. 
</P>
<P>
	But she also said the outcome of the affair could have been  
different had the president been more forthright about his efforts 
to distance himself from her in 1996 and 1997. That's when she was 
reassigned to a Pentagon job and was unable to win back a position 
at the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he has a desire to please everybody, and he is also an  
ostrich in that he avoids confrontation at all costs.'' She said it 
``would have changed things a lot'' if he had been more honest 
``instead of stringing me along.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky again denies that Clinton tried to buy her silence  
or otherwise obstruct justice, a charge that led to his 
impeachment. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she didn't discuss with Clinton the writing of an  
affidavit in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit in which she 
denied having had a sexual relationship with him. She also denies 
in Time that Clinton and his friend Vernon Jordan helped her job 
search in exchange for her silence. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mrs. Tripp, who exposed the affair by giving Independent  
Counsel Kenneth Starr tapes of her phone conversations with Ms. 
Lewinsky, said Ms. Lewinsky made clear in untaped conversations 
that there was a deal in the works. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was instructed by both the president and Vernon Jordan  
that she had no choice but to use the, quote, story, the cover 
story,'' Mrs. Tripp maintained. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the Lewinsky interview and the highly publicized book  
about her were ``Monica's self-justification of events in which she 
was complicit in bringing about.'' Asked about the book, she said, 
``I see it as fiction. I see it as fable, fantasy, farce and fairy 
tale. I see almost no bearing on reality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp, who was present when Starr's staff and FBI officials  
first questioned Ms. Lewinsky about the affair in a Washington 
hotel, said Ms. Lewinsky's assertions that she was mistreated and 
denied access to a lawyer were ``completely false.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also scoffed at Ms. Lewinsky's statements that she was  
mortified by the prominence given the blue dress stained in one of 
her encounters with Clinton. ``This was a badge of honor for 
Monica,'' Mrs. Tripp said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, asked about the Lewinsky  
interview on ``Fox News Sunday,'' said, ``All I know is that what I 
saw and heard last week sort of reconfirmed in my mind that I cast 
the right vote in the Senate.'' Lott, R-Miss., voted to convict 
Clinton on both articles of impeachment, but the president 
acquitted on both charges of perjury and the obstruction of justice 
charge. 
</P>
<P>
	As to future action against the president for his alleged  
misconduct, Lott said: ``I think it's in the hands of the American 
people or, you know, what his conscience might dictate, which is 
apparently not much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky, in her Time interview, spoke of the way Clinton  
``looks at women he's attracted to. He undresses you with his 
eyes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also said that at her first book-signing event, ``I felt  
cuckoo. ... This whole situation is sort of maniacal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said that in the future she might consider law school, ``if  
I could get into law school without having to take the LSAT,'' the 
aptitude test for prospective law students. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she was not trying to get rich with her book deal and  
other paid appearances. ``But I need to have the means to take care 
of myself for the next few years,'' she said. ``Therapy is not 
cheap.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
