<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990307.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 12:13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Steelmakers Criticize Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- In a building as long as three soccer fields, a  
thick slab of steel slides out of a blazing furnace, orange with 
heat. 
</P>
<P>
	Sparks fly and chunks of nearly molten metal drop to the floor  
as it rattles along a conveyer toward the first of six machines 
that will squeeze the hot steel between giant rollers, gradually 
flattening it into a sheet less than an inch thick and 180 feet 
long. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the Kimitsu Steel Works, one of Japan's biggest  
producers of hot-rolled steel. The United States used to be its 
largest foreign market, but that was before steel became the 
subject of the latest trade fight between Tokyo and Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, none of the half dozen freighters snugged to Kimitsu's  
docks is bound for North America. Sales to the Americans have 
nearly dried up with the U.S. government considering imposition of 
penalty duties on Japanese steel for allegedly being ``dumped'' at 
below-manufacturing cost. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very worried,'' said Noritoshi Kimura, a senior manager  
at Kimitsu Works. ``The suit comes just as the economy is turning 
bad and demand is shrinking. The timing was terrible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With no sign of recovery from a recession at home, and most of  
Japan's neighbors struggling with their own economic crises, demand 
for steel is severely depressed throughout Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Europe has never been a major destination for Japanese exports.  
The U.S. market has been, and producers in Japan say they are being 
unfairly shut out. 
</P>
<P>
	``To say that Japanese steel exports have hurt the U.S. market  
is completely wrong. It's unreasonable. Japan has been made a 
scapegoat,'' said Hiroki Sasaki, a member of the board of directors 
for the world's second-largest steelmaker, Nippon Steel. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. steel industry filed a dumping complaint against  
Japanese competitors after their U.S. sales surged last year to 2 1/2 
times the 1997 level. The dramatic rise, along with a jump in 
imports from South Korea, Brazil and Russia, was blamed for 
thousands of U.S. layoffs and three company bankruptcies. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Commerce Department said last month that Japanese  
producers were dumping hot-rolled steel at up to 68 percent below 
the fair value, and it threatened to impose punitive duties. 
</P>
<P>
	Nippon Steel never sold its products below cost, Sasaki  
contends. He says the company has been unable to defend itself 
against the charges because the Commerce Department won't say how 
it calculated its findings. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese industry executives argue that the drop in U.S. steel  
prices in 1998 was caused by market factors: a surge in demand for 
steel early in the year as the U.S. economy grew more robust, 
followed by a sudden collapse when General Motors plants went on 
strike. GM is the U.S. steel industry's largest customer. 
</P>
<P>
	Paralyzed by the prospect of stiff dumping duties, Japanese  
shipments of rolled steel to the United States plunged 99.7 percent 
in January from a year earlier to just 294 tons, Japan's Ministry 
of International Trade and Industry said last Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline is already hurting.  
</P>
<P>
	Kawasaki Steel Corp., one of the top five Japanese producers,  
increased the estimate of its expected loss for the fiscal year 
that ends March 31 by a third to $820 million. It blamed the trade 
dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, Japan's steelmakers predict they will have to cut  
output by about 10 percent this year, a huge blow to an industry 
that was already struggling with underused plants and too many 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Japanese steel market remains at this level, then some  
kind of drastic reorganization can be expected,'' said Seiji 
Yamada, a steel analyst for the investment bank Dresdner Kleinwort 
Benson. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry already had been cutting back for more than a  
decade. More than 3,200 jobs have been lost at the Kimitsu mill 
since 1986, reducing its workforce to 3,800. 
</P>
<P>
	The cuts have come from retirements and transfers of employees  
to affiliated firms, so Kimitsu and other big steel plants have 
avoided mass firings so far. 
</P>
<P>
	But senior manager Kimura, a 30-year veteran of the steel  
industry, is worried about the impact of the company's long hiring 
freeze. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been hiring so few new people, what is going to happen  
if demand grows stronger 10 years from now?'' he said. ``There 
won't be enough experienced managers to run the company.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990307.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 19:13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
