<HEADLINE> Statue Prompts Bus Route Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHELTON, Conn. (AP) -- A school bus route was changed for art's  
sake -- because one little girl could see more than she wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	The bus passed right by a 15-foot replica of Michelangelo's nude  
statue ``David'' standing in a private office park. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark DelVecchio said Sunday his 10-year-old daughter told him  
last week that she was offended by the statue, so he called her 
school and asked officials to change the bus route. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people think I'm ridiculous, but you've got to  
remember how tall a school bus is,'' said the father of three 
daughters. ``The view you actually get from the bus window is from 
the navel down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bus now passes out of sight of the statue, installed by the  
developer of the office complex. 
</P>
<P>
	DelVecchio said he has been unfairly accused of depriving  
children from art. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad the guy brought it. I'll probably never make it to  
Italy to see it,'' DelVecchio said. ``But you have to look at it 
through my daughter's eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they were looking at the guy's face, it would've been a  
different story.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
