<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Met Opera Presents 'Khovanshchina' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                  *An AP Arts and Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Metropolitan Opera audience, basically  
attuned to Verdi, is not in sync with Mussorgsky's sprawling, 
doom-ridden ``Khovanshchina.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The audience on Friday night was sparse and became increasingly  
so during the opera -- more than four hours long. 
</P>
<P>
	Conductor Valery Gergiev brought out to the fullest the beauty  
of the very melodic music and got the evening's largest applause. 
Dolora Zajick was fine as Marfa, who links all the opera's 
elements, and Roberto Scandiuzzi was excellent in the largest male 
role, Dosifei, leader of the Old Believers. Most of the other 
singers in the large cast had vocal wobbles. 
</P>
<P>
	One problem with the opera, which is set in the late 17th  
century in Moscow, is that it is episodic, which makes it hard to 
follow. In one scene, three men sit and talk politics a long time, 
which is tedious to watch. 
</P>
<P>
	Mussorgsky, who wrote his own libretto, depicts in order in the  
first three scenes three factions opposing Peter the Great, who was 
a child at the time. In the first scene, Paata Burchuladze, 
imposing and theatrical but with a distracting vocal wobble, 
portrays Prince Ivan Khovansky, leader of the militia, who wants a 
revolt to put his son Andrei on the throne. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrei wants to carry off Emma, a young German girl. Emily  
Pulley's protests ring high and clear. Unfortunately for the 
audience, Emma doesn't appear again. Andrei's fiancee, Marfa 
(Zajick), steps in to say how hurt she feels. 
</P>
<P>
	The second scene has Marfa as a fortuneteller, visiting Prince  
Golitsin (Vladimir Bogachov), foretelling his exile. He's an 
adviser to Sophia, Peter the Great's older sister, and represents 
her. Neither Sophia nor Peter could be depicted on stage in 
Mussorgsky's time. 
</P>
<P>
	The third scene concerns the Old Believers, with Marfa, a member  
of that religion, continuing to lament her love for Andrei. 
</P>
<P>
	Crashing chords of doom punctuate the opera. The last scenes  
depict disasters to Peter's opponents. Khovansky is shot. Golitsin, 
in a cart, rolls to exile. The Old Believers set their hermitage on 
fire and die singing at the final curtain. 
</P>
<P>
	There is a lot of glorious singing for a large chorus, almost no  
duet or small ensemble singing. Instead of a romantic couple there 
is Marfa's one-sided love. She tells Andrei she'll hide him after 
his father is shot. She takes him to die with her. He's still 
singing about Emma. 
</P>
<P>
	``Khovanshchina'' (Khovansky intrigue), last heard at the Met in  
1988, is being performed six times this season, including a March 
13 matinee live radio broadcast. Mussorgsky started composing it 
soon after he finished ``Boris Godunov.'' He died in 1881 before 
orchestrating it. Rimsky-Korsakov orchestrated it in 1883 and 
Shostakovich, whose orchestrations are used by the Met, did it in 
1958. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990307.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 15:31:59 </DATE_TIME>
