<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 10:23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Now the Target of Antitrust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a five-month Microsoft marathon, it is  
now Intel inside the antitrust courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	The microchip giant will take center stage Tuesday in an  
administrative law hearing at the Federal Trade Commission, 
contesting government charges it illegally used bullying tactics to 
quell competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The Intel case is not likely to have the entertainment value of  
that OTHER antitrust case, now on a month's recess at U.S. District 
Court down the block. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the Microsoft antitrust trial, there probably will not be  
any smoking gun e-mails. Nor will there be bitter disputes over 
what happened: Intel acknowledges it did most of what the FTC 
alleges; the company just claims it acted legally. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the lower profile, the Intel case carries high stakes  
that ultimately could affect prices, quality and innovation in 
computers millions of people now use. 
</P>
<P>
	The central issue in the government's complaint is whether Intel  
Corp., holds a monopoly in the market for microprocessors, the 
``brains'' of computers. The FTC says yes, because Intel microchips 
run about 80 percent of the world's computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal regulators must prove to the administrative judge  
hearing the case that Intel used monopoly power to shut out its 
competition, hurting consumers in the process. The government also 
must show how such actions curbed innovation and barred other 
companies' potential entry into the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel scoffs at the notion that it has ``chilled'' innovation.  
Indeed, the case opens as the company faces unprecedented 
competition from rival chipmakers, specifically Advanced Micro 
Devices Inc. and National Semiconductor Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of funny because the FTC has chosen to bring this  
case at probably the one time in the last 15 years where Intel 
really was having problems in the market,'' said Daniel Wall, an 
antitrust attorney in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tough argument (for Intel) to say they don't have  
monopoly power, but they're better positioned to make that argument 
now than they have ever been.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In its complaint, the government claims Intel illegally used its  
industry influence to withhold key technical information about 
future microchips from three companies: Digital Equipment Corp., 
Intergraph Corp., and Compaq Computer Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The information was necessary for the businesses to develop  
computer systems based on future Intel chips. The FTC claims Intel 
withheld the data to punish the companies for refusing to license 
key patents to Intel without charge. The patents are for 
microprocessors and related technologies made by the three 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Digital, which makes hardware and software, and Compaq, the  
world's largest computer maker, ultimately gave in to Intel. 
Intergraph, which makes specialized computers for engineers, sued 
and eventually got a preliminary injunction requiring Intel to turn 
over the information. Intel is appealing. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC, in court documents, calls Intel's actions ``a raw  
exercise of monopoly power to muscle competitors into signing over 
intellectual property rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Intel, which reported $26.2 billion in sales last year,  
acknowledges it denied the technical data, but argues it legally 
can decide which secrets to disclose to customers. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent industry report showed consumers bought more low-end  
computers in January with AMD processors than Intel -- knocking 
Intel from the No. 1 spot for the first time in that area. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel claims AMD's performance in the marketplace ``flies in the  
face'' of the government's theory. Two years ago, none of the top 
computer makers used AMD processors, it notes; today nine of the 
top 10 do. 
</P>
<P>
	``The evidence shows that competition has intensified greatly  
since the time of that conduct,'' the company said in court papers. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the FTC's economic expert, Harvard University professor  
Frederic M. Scherer, found no evidence that innovation in the 
computer industry has suffered, the company points out. 
</P>
<P>
	Scherer describes Intel's behavior as ``unfair'' but agrees that  
its actions have not directly affected chip prices, a factor in 
determining monopoly power. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC's antitrust case against Intel was filed shortly after  
the Justice Department and 19 states sued Microsoft, the software 
giant accused of abusing its monopoly power. The two federal 
agencies have overlapping authority on antitrust and typically 
divide cases. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Intel case, the FTC seeks a far more limited remedy, if  
it wins, than the ones contemplated for Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency wants an administrative order requiring Intel to stop  
withholding technical information from customers who develop rival 
technologies. Either side can appeal the administrative judge's 
ruling to the full FTC. If Intel loses there, it can go to a 
federal judge. 
</P>
<P>
	By comparison, a prominent technology industry group has  
suggested splitting Microsoft into separate companies selling 
different products, if a federal judges rules against the company. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990307.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 18:41:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles To Play in Cuba March 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Major league baseball is returning to Cuba for the first time in  
40 years, completing a deal Sunday in which the Baltimore Orioles 
will play the Cuban national team on March 28 in Havana. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this produces the kind of human results that we're all  
hoping it does, this could be something really big,'' baseball 
commissioner Bud Selig said. ``I'm very proud of the role we will 
play in doing something constructive -- that transcends baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cuban team will play a return exhibition game at Camden  
Yards. The second game will be played either just before Baltimore 
starts the regular season April 5 or on an off day during the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that they do come,'' Stanley Hynds, a 25-year-old  
barber, shouted amid the clanging steel drums, trumpet blares and 
impassioned screams during a playoff game in Latinoamericano 
Stadium in Havana on Sunday. ``It will be a pleasure for us to see 
them and to see them lose right here in this stadium!'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement came after two months of negotiations among the  
State Department, Cuban government, commissioner's office, the 
Orioles and the players' association. 
</P>
<P>
	The games were planned after the Clinton administration decided  
in January to ease the four-decade-old U.S. trade embargo against 
Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Major league baseball teams used to visit Cuba regularly, but  
the last were the Cincinnati Reds and Los Angeles Dodgers, who 
played exhibition games there in March 1959, about 2 1/2 months after 
Fidel Castro's revolution ousted dictator Fulgencio Batista on New 
Year's Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Selig, who plans to attend the game in Havana, said that if the  
game is successful, the major leagues might schedule additional 
events in Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are other clubs that want to do this, too,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Several Cubans have defected in recent years and play for major  
league teams, notably Florida pitcher Livan Hernandez, the 1997 
World Series MVP; his half-brother Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez, 
who starred for the New York Yankees in last year's postseason; and 
Tampa Bay pitcher Rolando Arrojo. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're very good players,'' Orioles outfielder B.J. Surhoff  
said. ``If you look around the majors, there are a number of very 
good players with Cuban backgrounds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Castro, Cuba's president and a former baseball player himself,  
has referred to defectors as ``traitors,'' and Cuban officials have 
accused U.S. teams of trying to bribe Cuban players into abandoning 
their country. U.S. agents have helped Cuban players defect when 
they were on tour outside their homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	Several hours after the announcement, news of the game had still  
not reached baseball-crazy Cubans in the capital of Havana. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's great! Finally we can test the strength of our  
players,'' said Jose Angel Montes, a 25-year-old computer 
technician, when informed of the agreement. ``We have a lot of 
players who are a lot better than Duque Hernandez.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While salaries in Cuba average $10 a month, Livan Hernandez got  
a four-year contract from the Marlins worth $4,495,000, and Orlando 
got a $6.6 million, four-year deal from the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban refugees and several congressmen have criticized baseball  
and the Orioles for dealing with Castro and oppose the games. About 
70 people protested Sunday at the Orioles' exhibition game against 
the Florida Marlins in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``Going to Cuba under the current conditions there is a sign of  
insensitivity and lack of respect for human rights there,'' said 
Huber Matos, a Cuban native who spent 20 years in prison on the 
island for opposing Castro's government. ``It's like taking part in 
the abuses that are going on there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Selig said he understands ``people have all kinds of different  
human and political views.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very sensitive to that. I understand the feelings,'' he  
said in Tampa, Fla. ``We'll take care of the baseball politics and 
let the governments take care of the other issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Proceeds from the two games -- a sticking point in the  
negotiations -- will be used mainly to support baseball and other 
sports activities in the two countries, major league baseball said. 
The Clinton administration did not want profits to go to Castro's 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Because it's only an exhibition game, Orioles' players won't put  
too much emphasis on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got things I need to get done on the field,'' first  
baseman Will Clark said. ``If I'm one of the guys who has to go 
down there, I'm going to treat it just like another ball game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the deal, two American League umpires and two Cuban  
umpires will work the game, and the Cuban team agreed to use wood 
bats instead of the metal bats it usually hits with, according a 
source familiar with the deal who spoke on the condition he not be 
identified. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles and the commissioner's office will pay for the  
improvements at Latinamericanos Stadium, such as padding the 
outfield fence, the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	A delegation from major league baseball, the players'  
association and the Orioles probably will go to Havana this week to 
work out logistics and attempt to settle when the game in Baltimore 
will be played. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990307.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 12:31:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greene Wins 60m at World Indoors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAEBASHI, Japan (AP) -- With one false start after another  
marring his earlier heats, Maurice Greene knew he had to keep calm 
to win the 60 meters Sunday at the World Indoor Track 
Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene proved he could do just that, winning the gold with a  
time of 6.42 seconds. His own world record is 6.39. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came here to win and I won,'' he said, adding that he never  
promised to set a new world record. ``I have to be satisfied with 
the win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Harden, who beat Greene at the USA Championships a week ago,  
won the silver, improving his best time by .01 of a second to 6.43. 
Jason Gardener of Great Britain placed third at 6.46. 
</P>
<P>
	In the women's 60 meters, Ekaterini Thanou of Greece beat  
American Gail Devers by .06 seconds to win the gold at 6.96. 
Devers, bothered by a hamstring injury throughout the races, 
clocked in at 7.02 seconds, slower than her indoor season best of 
6.98. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene said the false starts were not his fault but were caused  
by an unusually sensitive system at the three-day event that would 
register the slightest flinch or movement as a false start. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just trying to change for the system and just do the  
best job that I could,'' Greene said. ``I stayed focused and I ran 
a very technical good race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His coach, John Smith, said that the false starts, in the end,  
did not hurt Greene's running. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I wanted to him to do was get it out of his head and make  
him get back to the point where he can compete,'' Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Greene wasn't about to blame the false starts for not  
breaking the world record. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always possible to break the world record,'' he said.  
``But you know you have to run a technical race. I just didn't 
produce a world record race today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harden said he was extremely pleased with his race.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good race,'' he said. ``You're racing against the  
world-record holder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greene acknowledged Harden was ``improving each week.''  
</P>
<P>
	``Anything can happen in 60 meters,'' he said. ``You lose some  
and you win some. It's the life of being a sprinter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Devers' leg was so sore she sat on the floor during her news  
conference after the race, But the two-time indoor 60-meters 
champion appeared in good spirits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy to finish the race no worse than I started,'' said  
Devers, also a two-time world indoor champion and two-time Olympic 
gold medalist at 100 meters. 
</P>
<P>
	``She ran a great race,'' Devers said of Thanou.  
</P>
<P>
	Thanou said she was thrilled to win.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very happy for everyone in my country. And I hope with  
this medal, they'll all be happy, too,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
