<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sketches of Cent. American Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Presidents of the countries President Clinton is visiting in  
Central America: 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	NICARAGUA: President Arnoldo Aleman, 54, is a coffee grower who  
turned to politics and was elected mayor of Managua in 1990. He was 
once jailed for opposing the dictatorship of Anastasio Somoza, 
whose family ruled Nicaragua for 42 years, but also opposed the 
leftist Sandinistas who overthrew Somoza in 1979. He is the second 
conservative president after a decade of rule by the Sandinistas, 
which was marred by fighting against U.S.-supported Contra rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EL SALVADOR: President Armando Calderon Sol, 50, is a  
conservative who twice served as mayor of San Salvador before 
becoming president in 1994. Once a fierce opponent of the leftist 
guerrillas who fought for power from 1979 until 1992, Calderon Sol 
surprised many by his conciliatory attitude once elected. His term 
has been marked by attempts to improve El Salvador's 
war-impoverished economy. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HONDURAS: President Carlos Flores Facusse, 49, is a  
U.S.-educated industrial engineer who took office a year ago. He is 
the publisher of the newspaper La Tribuna. He strongly opposed the 
military, which ruled Honduras for decades, and served as a cabinet 
minister after the return to civilian rule in the 1980s before 
running unsuccessfully for president in 1989. He became leader of 
the legislature before running again and defeating the widow of a 
former military ruler. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GUATEMALA: President Alvaro Arzu, 53, is a  
businessman-turned-politician who worked in the tourism industry 
until 1986, when was elected mayor of Guatemala City. He served as 
foreign minister and director of the government's National Tourism 
Institute before being elected president in 1996. Early in his 
term, Arzu signed a peace agreement with leftist rebels that ended 
a 36-year civil war in which 150,000 people died and 50,000 
disappeared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
