<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iditarod Sled Dog Race Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASILLA, Alaska (AP) -- The dog teams are trained, the gear  
repaired and the trail scouted out. Now it's time for speed and 
strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday the 56 mushers in the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race  
headed into the Alaska wilderness, each with a game plan for being 
the first to reach the finish line in Nome, 1,100 miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	The mushers are competing for a $450,000 purse, of which $54,000  
goes to the winner. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner must have fast dogs. That goes without saying, and a  
dozen or more mushers fit that description. 
</P>
<P>
	It's trail savvy and tactics that will separate the elite from  
the also-rans -- when to run the team hard and when to ease up, how 
far to run between rests, how long to rest, and as the race 
progresses, when to make the decisive move. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at every champion -- we've all risked something to win  
this thing,'' said Doug Swingley of Lincoln. Mont., who won in 1995 
in a record 9 days, 3 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Swingley's bold venture that year was to push his team halfway  
down the trail, to the gold-mining ghost town of Iditarod, before 
taking his mandatory 24-hour rest stop. The other frontrunners 
followed conventional wisdom and took their long break much sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	Those mushers kept waiting for Swingley's dogs to run out of gas  
because they ran too hard too soon, but the collapse never 
happened. He ended up with a fresher, better-rested team and won 
the race by a comfortable six hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Swingley is not saying whether he'll run as far as Iditarod  
again this year, but that's not his point. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of guys are beating on the door, but (to win) they have  
to think of something new,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years the Iditarod has seen its share of innovations in  
sleds, harnesses, clothing and dog nutrition. 
</P>
<P>
	Now catching on is freeze-dried dog food -- blocks of desiccated  
beef, lamb, egg and other ingredients that when mixed with warm 
water creates a high-energy meal. 
</P>
<P>
	At $10 a pound, the food is much more expensive than the frozen  
meat that makes up most of the dogs' diet. But it's lighter, won't 
spoil and can be prepared more quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to be a necessity,'' said DeeDee Jonrowe,  
last year's runner-up. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'll see people a little less dependent on checkpoints,''  
said three-time champion Martin Buser. ``We're going to see more 
camping out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camping out along the trail is a tried-and-true Iditarod head  
game. When front-of-the-pack mushers are in a checkpoint, they can 
keep an eye on each other and be ready to respond to any move. But 
when they camp, they're less visible to the competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Swenson, a five-time Iditarod winner, said freeze-dried  
food would add a tactical twist on certain parts of the trail, but 
he's not using it. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you have a good, strong, healthy team, the weight of  
carrying fresh meat is not much of an issue,'' said Swenson, who 
last won the race in 1991. ``And I can prepare my fresh-frozen 
product as fast as freeze-dried.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Mackey, the 1983 Iditarod champion, is carrying  
freeze-dried food and expects to camp out more this year as a way 
to keep away from other mushers. 
</P>
<P>
	In doing so, he's also playing to his team's experience of  
running long distances without visiting a checkpoint. All of 
Mackey's dogs have done the 1,000-mile Yukon Quest International 
race. The Quest has fewer than half as many checkpoints as the 
Iditarod. 
</P>
<P>
	``My plan is to try to eliminate a few of the checkpoints,''  
Mackey said. ``I figure that's my only advantage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Iditarod commemorates a dog-sled relay of diphtheria serum  
to Nome during a 1925 epidemic. The race began in 1973 and is run 
along historic trails traveled by gold prospectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
