<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *J. Leland Atwood    	
</P>
<P>
	COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) -- J. Leland ``Lee'' Atwood, a key figure  
in the aerospace industry for more than 50 years while president 
and chief executive officer of Rockwell International Corp., died 
Friday. He was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood's work led to the development of the P-51 Mustang  
fighter, one of the main aircraft used in World War II. The fighter 
was developed for Rockwell's predecessor company North American 
Aviation, now part of the Boeing Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood was credited with helping the company gain leading roles  
in developing the award-winning F-100 Super Sabre, X-15 rocket 
plane, the B-1 bomber and space shuttle. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1934, he began work at North American Aviation, becoming  
chief engineer and vice president. He was elected president in 
1948, gaining the title of CEO in 1960 and then chairman of the 
company two years later. 
</P>
<P>
	He received various aviation awards, including a Presidential  
Certificate of Merit in 1948 for his contributions to the war 
effort. In 1995, Italy gave him its Commander of Merit declaration 
for his contributions to the aerospace industry. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1969, he was awarded NASA's Public Service Award, the highest  
honor for a non-governmental employee. It recognized his leadership 
efforts with the government-industry team that completed the first 
manned lunar orbit mission, Apollo 8. 

</P>
<P>
 *Leopold Just    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Leopold Just, a Latvian-born engineer who built  
a reputation worldwide for constructing highways and New York City 
bridges, died Feb. 25. He was 95. 
</P>
<P>
	Just helped design the George Washington Bridge, linking New  
York and New Jersey, and the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge, connecting 
Staten Island and Brooklyn. 
</P>
<P>
	He came to New York in 1921 and worked for the consulting firm  
Moran &AMP; Proctor before earning a civil engineering degree in 1929 
from the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn. He also held a law 
degree from New York University. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1931, Just joined what was then called the Port of New York  
Authority and helped design the Lincoln Tunnel. 
</P>
<P>
	He left in 1938 to build tunnels for the Pennsylvania Turnpike  
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Returning to New York in 1940 he became a structural engineer  
with the famed Swiss-born engineer, Othmar Ammann. 
</P>
<P>
	Just, who became a chief engineer in 1952, had a key part in  
designing the Walt Whitman Bridge in Philadelphia and the Throgs 
Neck Bridge, connecting the Bronx and Queens. 

</P>
<P>
 *Stanley Kubrick    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Stanley Kubrick, a visionary craftsman whose films  
-- including ``Dr. Strangelove,'' ``A Clockwork Orange'' and ``2001: 
A Space Odyssey'' -- often reflected a violent and despairing view 
of life, died Sunday. He was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Police were summoned Sunday to Kubrick's rural estate in  
Herfordshire, 25 miles northwest of London, and certified his 
death. ``There are no suspicious circumstances,'' police said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of his death, the publicity-shy Kubrick was  
preparing for the midyear release of ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' his first 
film in 12 years. Starring Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman, the film 
had been shrouded in the secrecy that attended all of Kubrick's 
later movies. 
</P>
<P>
	Over a career spanning four decades, Kubrick worked infrequently  
but often brilliantly, and was regarded as a maverick talent -- to 
some, a genius. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stanley Kubrick was the grandmaster of filmmaking. He copied  
no one, while all of us were scrambling to imitate him,'' director 
Steven Spielberg said in a statement released by his office. 
</P>
<P>
	Kubrick was a fierce perfectionist who wouldn't do one take if  
he could do a hundred. 
</P>
<P>
	Kubrick chronicled the effects of war in ``Fear and Desire''  
(1953) and ``Paths of Glory'' (1957); the suicidal logic of the 
Cold War in the blackly comic ``Dr. Strangelove: or, How I Learned 
To Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb'' (1964); and sexual obsession 
in ``Lolita'' (1962). 
</P>
<P>
	``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' with its dazzling visual imagery and  
inspired use of music, was a great success, and Kubrick got the 
second of his four Academy Award nominations for best director. The 
other nominations were for ``Dr. Strangelove,'' ``Barry Lyndon,'' 
and ``A Clockwork Orange,'' which unlike ``2001'' were also 
nominated for best picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``A Clockwork Orange,'' set in a violent future, was one of  
Kubrick's most provocative films and was disparaged by Anthony 
Burgess, whose novel was the basis of the film. Burgess accused 
Kubrick of turning his novelistic study of free will into an orgy 
of violence. 

</P>
<P>
 *Merrill Parks Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Merrill Parks Jr., the FBI's special  
agent in charge of Connecticut, died Saturday after a brief 
illness. He was 55. 
</P>
<P>
	Parks supervised about 100 agents and a support staff of 70  
since he was appointed to lead the Connecticut office in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	During his reign, the office brought charges against dozens of  
ranking members of the Latin Kings, the state's largest reputed 
gang. 
</P>
<P>
	Parks spent 29 years with the FBI, investigating organized crime  
in New York City, Houston and Washington. He spent two years in the 
early 1980s with the Drug Enforcement Agency. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990307.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 11:12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New WBA Champ To Have Eye Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- David Reid is looking toward a rich  
and successful boxing career, but first the new WBA super 
welterweight champion will have surgery on a droopy left eyelid. 
</P>
<P>
	The operation will be in five days and Reid can resume training  
in three or four weeks, said Dan Goosen, president of America 
Presents, Reid's promoter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Recovery time is minimal,'' Goosen said after Reid, the only  
U.S. Olympic boxing champion in 1996, outpointed Laurent Boudouani 
of France on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	This will be the third time Reid has had surgery on the lid, and  
it appears this sort of procedure will have to be done 
occasionally. 
</P>
<P>
	The droopy lid limits Reid's vision, but it didn't hamper his  
performance against Boudouani before a crowd of a crowd of 2,167, 
mostly Reid fans, in a ballroom at the Boardwalk Convention Center 
and before an HBO audience. 
</P>
<P>
	Boudouani scored with several hard rights to the head.  
</P>
<P>
	``I could see out of the left eye, but that right hand was  
coming fast,'' Reid said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid, a 25-year-old from Philadelphia, was simply too fast for  
his 32-year-old opponent. He was effective with jabs and rights to 
the body and he hurt the Frenchman with a left hook to the head 
that him wobbling in the ninth round. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew I hurt him, but he had enough experience to stay away,  
to stay up,'' said Reid, who won by six points each on two cards 
and by five on the third. 
</P>
<P>
	While the victory was not nearly as dramatic as his one-punch  
knockout of Cuba's Alfredo Duvergel in the third round of the 
156-pound gold-medal bout at the Atlanta Olympics in which he was 
far behind in the scoring, it was impressive for a man fighting 
professionally for only the 11th time. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid (11-0, seven knockouts, 154 pounds) did some trash talking,  
but Boudouani (38-3-1, 32 knockouts, 152 pounds), doesn't 
understand English. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid's next opponent is not known, but Boudouani, who said he  
hurt his left shoulder early in the fight, called for a rematch. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Reid is a gentleman, and I came all the way to this  
country,'' Boudouani said through an interpreter. ``If David Reid 
is a gentleman, maybe he will come all the way to France.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a 10-round heavyweight brawl, 6-foot-5 Lou Savarese, 240, of  
Houston got up from a sixth-round knockdown and scored a split 
decision over 6-8 Lance Whitaker, 249, who had won his first 18 pro 
fights, 16 by knockout. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitaker's camp contended that Savarese (39-2, 32 knockouts)  
didn't beat referee Steve Smoger's 10-count. Savarese, however, 
while on one knee, looked directly at Smoger as he took the count, 
and it appeared he got up before 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990307.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 15:13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Band in Berlin' Is Misguided </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It is odd to spend 90 minutes-plus with a group  
of performers and then not learn much about the characters they are 
playing -- despite a proliferation of facts. 
</P>
<P>
	Such an experience occurs in ``Band in Berlin,'' a misguided  
musical documentary that somehow has found its way to Broadway and 
the Helen Hayes Theater. 
</P>
<P>
	The production combines the worst elements of educational  
television and a high school history lecture in its attempt to tell 
the story of the Comedian Harmonists, the most popular singing 
group in Germany before World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	There should be a stirring tale in this saga of six men -- five  
singers and a pianist -- whose unique five-part harmony gains them 
international fame. At the height of their popularity, they are 
forced to disband because several members of the group are Jewish. 
</P>
<P>
	The show's creators never quite resolve how they want the story  
told. The author, Susan Feldman, places the musical within a series 
of concerts given by the troupe between 1927 and 1935. In between 
songs, there are badly lighted and hokey film segments of an actor 
playing one of the singers as an old man, reminiscing about the 
past. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the musical numbers are fun, with the quaint  
old-fashioned style actually sounding fresh and new. The songs 
cover quite a lot of ground -- from sprightly German tunes to 
American standards such as ``Tea for Two,'' ``Stormy Weather'' and 
``It Don't Mean a Thing If It Ain't Got That Swing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The five singers -- first tenor Mark Bleeke, second tenor Timothy  
Leigh Evans, lyric baritone Hugh Munday, baritone Peter Becker and 
bass Wilbur Pauley -- work together in style. There is gentle fun in 
their performing, an almost sweet humor that is appealing. 
</P>
<P>
	Their best -- and wittiest -- moment occurs in a vocal  
interpretation of Rossini's overture to ``The Barber of Seville.'' 
Their voices really do sound like musical instruments. 
</P>
<P>
	Director Patricia Birch uses actual photographs, posters and art  
from the period to chronicle Germany's descent into Nazism. There 
is the obvious juxtaposition of the approaching firestorm with the 
cheerful, often exuberant melodies being sung on stage. It is a 
pattern that gets repeated over and over again with diminishing 
dramatic effect. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, ``Band in Berlin,'' too small and too studious for  
Broadway, would work better as a cabaret act. It is earnest 
entertainment, and despite the wonderful harmony, decidedly minor 
key. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
