<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Facts About Nicaragua, El Salvador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Facts about Nicaragua and El Salvador, which President Clinton  
is visiting Monday: 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *NICARAGUA:   	
</P>
<P>
	GEOGRAPHY: Covering 50,180 square miles, Nicaragua borders  
Honduras to the north and Costa Rica to the south. It has coasts on 
both the Pacific and Caribbean sides of Central America. 
</P>
<P>
	PEOPLE: Nicaragua's population of 4.3 million is overwhelmingly  
Roman Catholic, and Spanish is the official language -- except on 
the Miskito Coast along the Caribbean, where English is prevalent 
and there is a strong Protestant minority. 
</P>
<P>
	ECONOMY: With a mixture of mining and agriculture, Nicaragua  
produces coffee, sugar cane, corn, beans and cattle as well as 
lumber, gold, silver, copper, tungsten, lead and zinc. 
</P>
<P>
	HISTORY: Spanish conquerors first visited what is now Nicaragua  
in 1522 and it was a colony until it gained independence in 1838. 
The United States invaded in 1909 and occupied Nicaragua until 
1925, when it left Gen. Anastasio Somoza Garcia as president. The 
Somoza family ruled Nicaragua with an iron fist for 42 years. A 
popular uprising led by the leftist Sandinista movement took power 
in 1979. With U.S. aid, former Somoza soldiers mounted a nine-year 
guerrilla war. After a peace agreement in 1989, the Sandinistas 
lost the elections. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *EL SALVADOR:   	
</P>
<P>
	GEOGRAPHY: El Salvador covers 8,260 square miles, roughly the  
size of Massachusetts. It is bordered by Guatemala to the west and 
Honduras to the north and east, and has a Pacific coastline. 
</P>
<P>
	PEOPLE: The nation's 5.8 million people are largely Roman  
Catholic, but there is a growing Protestant minority. The language 
is Spanish. 
</P>
<P>
	ECONOMY: With a mixture of agriculture and industry, El Salvador  
produces coffee, cotton, corn, sugar, bananas, rice, beans and 
sorghum. It also processes foods, makes textiles and clothing and 
has major hydro-electric plants. 
</P>
<P>
	HISTORY: Spanish explorer Pedro de Alvarado conquered what is  
now El Salvador in 1525 and it was a colony until 1821, when the 
Central American nations formed a federation. El Salvador became a 
republic in 1838, but was oppressively ruled by an upper class 
closely allied with the rightist military. In 1979, a leftist 
guerrilla group launched a fight for power that lasted until 1992, 
when a peace agreement was signed. A republican government is now 
in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
