<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Economics To Be Studied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Baseball's latest economic study committee --  
this one with members picked only by the owners -- starts work with 
a Monday meeting in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, former Federal  
Reserve chairman Paul Volcker, Yale president Richard Levin and 
television commentator George Will are the four outsiders on the 
group. Levin was the author of the owners' original salary cap 
proposal in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Bud Selig heads the panel, and Colorado Rockies  
owner Jerry McMorris and Boston Red Sox chief executive officer 
John Harrington are the vice chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Selig appointed the ``blue ribbon task force'' last month after  
many owners complained the latest salary escalation further 
increased the imbalance between baseball's haves and have nots. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball's current collective bargaining agreement probably will  
expire after the 2001 season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
