<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UN Criticizes INS Refugee Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States' clampdown on illegal  
immigration is hurting would-be asylum seekers and refugees, 
complains a high-ranking representative of the U.N. High 
Commissioner for Refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	People fleeing persecution in their homelands are being snared  
in a web of ``very, very restrictive'' U.S. policies designed to 
deter illegal immigration, said Dennis McNamara, director of the 
division of international protection at the Geneva-based 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. agency is responsible for overseeing the safety of the  
world's refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	McNamara was in Washington in recent days to meet with officials  
of the State Department and elsewhere. He was registering 
objections to U.S. detention and removal policies Congress ordered 
under a 1996 law designed to crack down on illegal immigration. 
</P>
<P>
	He planned to meet Monday with Doris Meissner, commissioner of  
the Immigration and Naturalization Service, and suggest 
alternatives to the detention of would-be refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they are refugees, of course they should not be detained at  
all unless they are a threat to the state or community,'' he said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The detention and removal policies are ``on a par with some of  
the most restrictive that we have seen in industrialized 
countries,'' McNamara said. 
</P>
<P>
	INS officials defended their handling of the more than 100,000  
asylum and refugee cases considered each year. 
</P>
<P>
	About 5,000 people temporarily are detained because they arrived  
without documents or with fraudulent papers, INS spokesman Barbara 
Francis said. She said 40 percent are released before their cases 
are completed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States has one of the most generous asylum programs  
in the world,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	McNamara agreed the United States has a good record in offering  
political haven. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. remains our major donor, financial supporter, major  
political backer (and) .... the biggest refugee receiving country 
in the world. So the record is a long and positive one in general 
terms for refugees,'' McNamara said. ``Even more, therefore, our 
concern that these new restrictions go against that general 
trend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 law put in place procedures that require the temporary  
detention of would-be asylum seekers and refugees who present 
themselves at U.S. ports of entry without travel documents or with 
false paperwork. They are detained during investigation of their 
claim. 
</P>
<P>
	McNamara said such detention constitutes a breach of the  
international refugee convention signed by the United States and 
135 other nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``The refugee convention says that people should not be punished  
for illegally entering the country, and that includes detention,'' 
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
