<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Rockwell CEO Atwood Dies at 94 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) -- J. Leland ``Lee'' Atwood, a key figure  
in the aerospace industry for more than 50 years while president 
and chief executive officer of Rockwell International Corp., has 
died. He was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood died Friday of natural causes at St. John's Hospital in  
Santa Monica, the company announced Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	His work led to the development of the P-51 Mustang fighter, one  
of the main aircraft used in World War II. The fighter was 
developed for Rockwell's predecessor company North American 
Aviation, now part of the Boeing Co. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lee was a great American and his contributions during this  
century helped enable the United States to attain aerospace 
superiority,'' Don H. Davis, Rockwell's chairman and chief 
executive officer, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood was credited with helping the company gain leading roles  
in developing the award-winning F-100 Super Sabre, X-15 rocket 
plane, the B-1 bomber and Space Shuttle. 
</P>
<P>
	The engineer was born in Walton, Ky. on Oct. 26, 1904. He  
studied at Hardin-Simmons University and later received a 
bachelor's of science degree in civil engineering from the 
University of Texas in 1928. 
</P>
<P>
	He started his career as a junior airplane engineer with the  
Army Air Corps at Wright Field in Dayton, Ohio in 1928. Two years 
later he left to work as a design engineer with Douglas Aircraft 
Co. in Santa Monica. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1934, he began work at North American Aviation, becoming  
chief engineer and vice president. He was elected president in 
1948, gaining the title of CEO in 1960 and then chairman of the 
company two years later. 
</P>
<P>
	He received various aviation awards, including a Presidential  
Certificate of Merit in 1948 for his contributions to the war 
effort. In 1995, Italy gave him its Commander of Merit declaration 
for his contributions to the aerospace industry. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1969, he was awarded NASA's Public Service Award, the highest  
honor for a non-governmental employee. It recognized his leadership 
efforts with the government-industry team which completed the first 
manned lunar orbit mission, Apollo 8. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood is survived by his wife, Patricia.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
