<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pfeiffer Says Women Are Heroes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Michelle Pfeiffer thinks the obstacles women  
face in life make them great role models. 
</P>
<P>
	``Women are the heroes of our time,'' Pfeiffer says in Sunday's  
Daily News. ``We accept the impossible. We take on way more than we 
could ever accomplish, and we somehow manage to do it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Think about it. We run the home. We pretty much are in charge  
of raising the children, although the men help. A lot of us have 
careers. Also, women are very much in charge of putting energy into 
a relationship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pfeiffer's latest movie, ``The Deep End of the Ocean,'' is a  
tear-jerker about a woman whose young son disappears from a hotel 
lobby. 
</P>
<P>
	The 41-year-old actress, whose films include ``A Thousand  
Acres,'' ``The Age of Innocence,'' ``Batman Returns,'' ``The 
Fabulous Baker Boys,'' ``Dangerous Liaisons'' and ``Scarface,'' 
credits her good looks for getting her career going, but said hard 
work is what kept it going. 
</P>
<P>
	``My appearance helped me in the beginning just to get work when  
I was learning my craft,'' she said. ``I learned to act as I went 
along. Learning on the job was a gift. It was also scary. 
Fortunately I have a real sink-or-swim mentality. I'm so afraid of 
humiliating myself that I'll go to any length not to.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
