<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose Monday amid continued bullish  
sentiment following a 5 percent rally in the market's main index 
Friday and a new record high on Wall Street. The dollar edged lower 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 95.75  
points, or 0.64 percent, to 14,989.75 points in the first 30 
minutes of trading. On Friday, the average closed up 710.55 points, 
or 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.82 yen in early trading, down 0.12 yen  
from late Friday in Tokyo but slightly above its New York level of 
122.80 yen late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices moved higher behind the yen's  
relative weakness against the dollar and continued low interest 
rates in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Also supporting the Tokyo market was Friday's 268.68-point gain  
in the Dow Jones industrial average for a new closing high of 
9,736.08. 
</P>
<P>
	New York stocks surged as a slight rise in joblessness and wages  
in the United States eased investor concerns that the fast-growing 
economy would spur inflation and higher interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 9.64 points, or 0.84 percent, to 1,156.36 
points. The TOPIX closed up 41.61 points, or 3.76 percent, on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar was slightly higher in Tokyo  
from Friday's level in New York after falling on profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	Players were watching the outcome of the Bank of Japan's policy  
board meeting slated for Friday, as speculation has mounted that 
the central bank may come up with more ways to ease its 
already-loose monetary policy. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the central bank's generous stance in the short-term  
money market has recently pushed down long-term interest rates in 
Japan, adding a boost to the dollar's strength against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 133.08 yen, up from  
132.98 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese  
government bond fell to 1.555 percent from Friday's finish of 1.560 
percent, driving its price up to 101.98 yen from 101.94 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
