<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton To Visit Central America  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Making a pilgrimage to the sites of Hurricane  
Mitch's worst horrors, President Clinton proffers Central Americans 
hope for their reconstruction so that despair does not turn into 
political trouble for the region. The president embarks Monday on 
his four-day, four-nation mission just as 15,000 Guatemalans and 
Salvadorans in the United States illegally become eligible for 
deportation. He has turned down pleas for an extension of the halt 
in deportations that was instituted after last fall's devastating 
storm and expires Monday. 

</P>
<P>
	Rightists Lead El Salvador Election  
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- An ex-philosophy professor was  
headed for a first-round victory in El Salvador's presidential 
election on Sunday with a strong lead over two former guerilla 
chiefs. With about 79 percent of votes counted, the Supreme 
Electoral Tribunal said Francisco Flores of the governing rightist 
National Republican Alliance had 51.8 percent -- enough to avoid a 
runoff against the No. 2 vote-getter if that share held up. Turnout 
appeared to be below 40 percent of the 3.1 million registered 
voters -- perhaps in response to a tepid campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	Turkish Troops Said Killed by Kurds  
</P>
<P>
	DIYARBAKIR, Turkey (AP) -- Kurdish rebels claimed Sunday they  
shot down an army helicopter, killing 20 Turkish soldiers, a 
Kurdish news agency reported. The German-based DEM reported that 
all aboard the helicopter died in the southeastern province of 
Hakkari. The rebels recently vowed that their fight for autonomy 
would escalate in defiance of the recent capture of their leader, 
Abdullah Ocalan. 

</P>
<P>
	Caribbean Suspends U.S. Treaty  
</P>
<P>
	PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) -- In an effort to fight drug  
trafficking, Caribbean Community nations have agreed to suspend a 
treaty of cooperation with the United States, an official said 
Sunday. The decision was fueled by anger over the U.S. position in 
a trade dispute over banana exports to Europe. The dispute 
escalated last week as the United States announced plans to impose 
punitive tariffs on targeted European goods. The WTO is holding an 
emergency meeting tomorrow to discuss the spreading trade dispute. 

</P>
<P>
	Benigni, Paltrow Win SAG Awards  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- An exuberant Roberto Benigni captured a lead  
actor prize for ``Life is Beautiful'' and Gwyneth Paltrow took home 
an actress award that she dedicated to her mother at the Screen 
Actors Guild awards Sunday night. Robert Duvall and Kathy Bates 
also received honors. Benigni's award was the biggest surprise of 
the night and suggested the best actor Oscar later this month is a 
toss-up. Paltrow was awarded for her role as the heiress who falls 
in love with a young William Shakespeare in ``Shakespeare in 
Love.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Japan's Justice Minister Resigns  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese Justice Minister Shozaburo Nakamura  
submitted his resignation amid a controversy over permitting actor 
Arnold Schwarzenegger to enter the country without passport. 
Nakamura's resignation was accepted by Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi 
on Monday morning, said a secretary in Nakamura's office. Nakamura 
has been criticized since going public with complaints about 
Japan's pacifist constitution and America's economic policy and his 
alleged involvement in a real estate scandal. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Close Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks closed lower Monday. The Nikkei  
shed 114.95 points to close at 14,779.05. 

</P>
<P>
	Timberwolves 88, SuperSonics 77  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Kevin Garnett had 19 points and 14 rebounds, and  
reserve Malik Sealy added a season-high 18 points as Minnesota 
handed Seattle its third straight loss, 88-77 Sunday night. Gary 
Payton scored 20 points on 9-for-27 shooting for the Sonics, who 
are 3-7 after a 6-0 start. Minnesota bounced back after a Friday 
night loss in Portland to win for the third time in four games. 

</P>
<P>
	NCAA Unveils Tournament Seedings  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- The Big Ten tied the record Sunday with  
seven teams selected for the 64-team NCAA tournament. The 
Southeastern Conference grabbed most of the top spots, however, 
with one-fourth of the top 16 seeds. Top-ranked Duke, Michigan 
State, Auburn and Connecticut were named No. 1 seeds. In addition 
to regular-season and tournament champion Michigan State, the other 
Big Ten teams selected were Ohio State, Indiana, Iowa, Minnesota, 
Wisconsin and Purdue. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
</P>
