<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 11:41:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Small Stocks Don't Draw a Crowd / Ticker Talk  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Raise the subject of small-company growth  
stocks at an investment conference these days, and you won't put 
yourself in any danger of being trampled in a stampede. 
</P>
<P>
	At a bustling annual gathering of some 850 financial advisers  
held here recently by the brokerage firm of Waterhouse Securities, 
a session on small-stock mutual funds drew a trickle-in audience of 
50 or so. 
</P>
<P>
	There's no mystery why the other 800 found something better to  
do. Small stocks have consistently trailed far behind the big blue 
chips all through the mid- to late 1990s, and they have shown no 
signs of behaving any differently so far this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an area of the market that has just been beaten up  
incredibly in recent times,'' said Ted Aronson, a specialist in 
small stocks with the money-management firm of Aronson and 
Partners, who took part in one of the conference's main panel 
discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	A case can be made, Aronson suggested, that small stocks have  
been stuck in the out-of-favor side of the investment cycle for the 
past 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Are we coming to a new small-cap cycle? I don't know,'' said  
James Oberweis, who manages three portfolios of small to mid-sized 
stocks at the firm of Oberweis Asset Management. But if you can't 
predict what the market will do next, he said, you can analyze the 
relative values that prevail today: ``Small-cap stocks are at an 
absolute all-time low relative to the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Traditionally, small stocks as a group trade at a higher  
price-earnings ratio than big stocks do, based on the presumption 
that small companies, working from a smaller base, can usually 
achieve faster earnings growth than their blue-chip counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	Lately, Oberweis noted, the aggregate P-E of a widely recognized  
small-stock index, the Russell 2,000, has been about 10 percent 
BELOW the P-E of the blue-chip-dominated S&AMP;P 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Many commentators say this represents an emotional extreme, and  
the pendulum must sooner or later swing back. Not every analyst and 
money manager agrees with this point of view, however -- some assert 
that blue chips have earned their new preeminence by emerging as 
the big winners in a new economic world order. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever their disagreements on other subjects, all the managers  
at the Waterhouse conference shared the same view of one category 
of investments, the super-hot Internet stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is insanity,'' said Oberweis. ``These stocks don't make  
any sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They strike me as the riskiest investments I've ever seen in  
my career,'' declared Robert Sanborn, manager of the Oakmark Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	``The math doesn't work,'' said Brian Posner, a celebrated  
manager at Fidelity Investments for 10 years before he took over 
the reins of the Warburg Pincus Growth &AMP; Income Fund in January 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Whitman, the outspoken manager of the Third Avenue Funds,  
suggested whimsically that the only sensible way to ride the 
Internet boom was to be a venture capitalist, putting your money 
into a small company before it goes public and cashing out when the 
initial public offering of stock is made. 
</P>
<P>
	Venture-capital investing is a high-risk proposition normally  
open only to wealthy investors who can afford to make numerous big 
bets at the same time, expecting no more than a few to pay off. 
</P>
<P>
	Aronson offered a different Internet-stock suggestion, also for  
bold types willing to go against the trend in the market: ``I think 
the way to play them is to sell them short.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
