<DOCNO> APW19990307.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 17:23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Clinton Aide Writes Memoirs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a new book, former White House aide George  
Stephanopoulos says he sought counseling and eventually took an 
antidepressant drug to help him deal with the pressures of ``living 
on the Clinton roller coaster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephanopoulos, who joined Clinton's campaign in 1991 and worked  
in the White House until late 1996, writes in his memoirs that he 
began seeing a therapist after White House counsel Vince Foster's 
suicide. He broke into hives, which he tried to hide with a beard, 
and suffered from insomnia. 
</P>
<P>
	He eventually saw a psychiatrist who prescribed Zoloft, a  
popular antidepressant, to ``help stop my nerves from flooding my 
brain with the chemical fueling my compulsive symptoms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The medication helped, Stephanopoulos said. ``I still worked  
hard, but I worried less. I cared about what we could do, but I 
didn't obsess.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephanopoulos also said he ``felt like a dupe'' when he learned  
the truth about Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	He writes that he doubted Clinton's denials when the Lewinsky  
scandal broke in January 1998 and says he wrestled with what he 
knew would be the consequences of feeling the way he did. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't believe Clinton, and I couldn't buy the party line --  
which meant I was the enemy now,'' Stephanopoulos wrote. ``I didn't 
think I was a hypocrite, because my defense of Clinton against past 
bimbo eruptions had been predicated on my belief that he wouldn't 
create new ones ... For several years, I had served as Clinton's 
character witness. Now I felt like a dupe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephanopoulos' book, ``All Too Human: A Political Education,''  
was excerpted in the latest issue of Newsweek magazine, available 
on newsstands Monday. The memoirs arrive in bookstores nationwide 
on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other tidbits from the former White House communications  
director, now a professor at Columbia University and an ABC News 
commentator: 
</P>
<P>
	--He said both Clintons had awesome tempers. ``When Hillary was  
angry, you didn't always know it right away -- a calculated chill 
would descend over time. Clinton's anger was a more impersonal 
physical force, like a tornado. The tantrum would form in an 
instant and exhaust itself in a violent rush. Whoever happened to 
be in the way would have to deal with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--His first impression of Clinton in 1991: ``An overgrown boy.  
... He had the gait of a man used to being obeyed, admired, courted 
and loved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--He did not challenge Clinton when Clinton's affair with  
Gennifer Flowers was revealed: ``I needed Clinton to see me as his 
defender, not his interrogator, which made me, of course, an 
enabler.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Once, during a brainstorming session about Supreme Court  
nominees, Clinton joked about nominating the first lady: ``The 
wildest fantasy hit closest to home: Wouldn't Hillary look great in 
a black robe? Of course, that couldn't happen ... '' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephanopoulos describes the Clintons as ``complete partners,  
businesslike in meetings, often childlike with each other.'' He 
describes seeing the Clintons in a playful stance one night in 1992 
when Clinton was ``hoarse and cranky'' while preparing for a 
debate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went up to their suite with the next day's schedule to find  
her on the couch with him, legs laid over his lap, feeding him 
lemon slices dipped in honey,'' Stephanopoulos said. ``In playful 
moments, Clinton called for her in baby talk: `Hee-a-ree, 
Hee-a-ree.' ... '' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
