<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGwire Hits First Spring Home Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JUPITER, Fla. (AP) -- Big Mac is on the board.  
</P>
<P>
	Mark McGwire hit his first home run of 1999, a three-run shot  
Sunday for the St. Louis Cardinals in an exhibition game against 
the Montreal Expos. 
</P>
<P>
	A sellout crowd at Roger Dean Stadium got exactly what it wanted  
when McGwire launched a long drive that easily cleared the 
left-field wall in the second inning. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire, coming off a record 70 homers last season, connected  
against rookie lefty Ted Lilly. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire had a slight smile after he stepped on home plate. J.D.  
Drew, Carlos Baerga and several other Cardinals greeted him, but 
McGwire did not punctuate this homer with his fake punch-to-the-gut 
routine that became his trademark during his historic season. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6,500-plus fan, many of them wearing No. 25 McGwire jerseys,  
responded with a standing ovation 
</P>
<P>
	The All-Star first baseman picked on a familiar opponent in the  
Expos. He hit his final five homers last year against them, and six 
overall. 
</P>
<P>
	Big Mac, who hit seven homers in spring training last season,  
was playing his second exhibition game of the year. He was 0-for-1 
and hit by a pitch against Montreal on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire hit a long foul before drawing a full-count walk from  
Jeremy Powell in the first inning. Against Lilly, McGwire barely 
missed a home run with a long drive that barely hooked foul before 
hitting a 2-1 pitch deep to left. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire did not bat again and left the game after three innings  
with the Cardinals ahead 6-0. He stopped in the left-field corner 
to sign autographs for a few minutes before walking to the 
clubhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	All but one of the Cardinals' 14 home exhibition games is sold  
out at Roger Dean Stadium, a complex they share with Montreal. 
McGwire merchandise dominates the souvenir stand, with hats, 
shirts, posters and model bats on sale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
