<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 19:33:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida A&AMP;M's Reward: Duke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Welcome to the big time, Florida A&AMP;M.  
</P>
<P>
	It promises to be a short and painful stay.  
</P>
<P>
	By pulling upset after upset last week in the Mid-Eastern  
Athletic Conference tournament, the Rattlers (12-18) got the NCAA 
bid they had been praying for. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, with that comes something of a sobering challenge: a  
first-round game against top-seeded Duke (32-1). 
</P>
<P>
	``If someone would have told me six months, or even six weeks  
ago, that we would be playing in the NCAA tournament against Duke, 
I would have laughed,'' Florida A&AMP;M coach Mickey Clayton said 
Sunday after watching the brackets announced on TV. 
</P>
<P>
	There hadn't been much to smile about around the A&AMP;M program  
until last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rattlers opened the season with 10 straight losses, the  
second-worst start in team history, and were 1-13 at one point. 
</P>
<P>
	But they turned their season around by going 11-5 the rest of  
the way despite injuries. In fact, they played the final of the 
MEAC tournament with just nine healthy bodies. 
</P>
<P>
	They managed to string together four straight wins as a No. 7  
seed last week and made their first-ever NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just have to continue to play together,'' said Jamaal  
Rhodes, a sophomore forward who will probably get the honor of 
covering Elton Brand next Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been branded the Cinderella through the conference  
tournament and we'll keep that moniker in this game as well. But we 
aren't afraid of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If history is any indicator, maybe they should be.  
</P>
<P>
	Since the NCAA expanded the tournament to 64 teams in 1985, a  
No. 16 seed has never beaten a top seed. Naturally, that means a 
team with a losing record has never had even one victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's miracle entry -- Prairie View -- brought its 13-16  
record to the tournament and was unceremoniously dumped 110-52 by 
Kansas in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Based in Tallahassee, also the home of Florida State, Florida  
A&AMP;M is used to standing well outside the sports spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	For at least one day, that will change for the Rattlers, as they  
trade in the Hampton States and Howards of the world for Duke, 
considered by far the strongest team in this year's tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Their only similar experience this year was a season-opening  
game against Auburn that ended in a 94-47 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope to draw from that experience,'' Clayton said. ``We're  
just going to go after these guys and see what happens.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
